column168: Description Of Events

INCIDENT REPORT:  AN AARON OIL COMPANY (AOC) DRIVER WAS IN THE PROCESS OF PUMPING OUT THE DROP IN LUBE USED OIL TANK.  THE DRIVER'S INTENTION WAS TO PUMP THE OIL TO TANK 3 OF HIS TRUCK BUT THERE WAS A VALVE MALFUNCTION AND THE OIL WENT INTO TANK 1, OVERFILLING IT.  EXAMINATION OF THE VALVE AFTER THE INCIDENT AND CLEAN-UP INDICATED THE VALVE STEM HAD SHEARED LEAVING THE VALVE TO TANK ONE IN THE OPEN POSITION.  THE VALVE WAS REPLACED AND ALL OTHER VALVES INSPECTED WITH NO ADDITIONAL ISSUE IDENTIFIED.  APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS OF USED OIL DRAINED ONTO THE CEMENT OF THE CUSTOMER SITE WITH SOME OIL FLOWING ALONG THE CURBING INTO THE STREET.  THE DRIVER ESTIMATES THAT ONE GALLON OF PRODUCT GOT INTO A STORM DRAIN THE HAS ABOUT A 12 INCH SUMP THAT MUST FILL UP FIRST BEFORE THE DISCHARGE PIPE IS REACHED.  ALL USED OIL WAS CONTAINED IN THIS SUMP.  CLEAN-UP ACTIVITIES:  UPON REALIZATION OF THE PROBLEM, THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY STOPPED PUMPING OUT THE CUSTOMER TANK.  THE DRIVER THEN BEGAN CONTAINMENT AND CLEAN-UP OPERATIONS. STANDING USED OIL WAS PUMPED BACK INTO THE TRUCK.  ABSORBENT WAS SPREAD ON THE CONCRETE AND STREET TO ABSORB REMAINING RESIDUE.  THIS WAS SWEPT UP AND PLACED IN A DRUM.  THE AOC DRIVER'S SUPERVISOR REPORTED TO THE SCENE BRINGING ADDITIONAL SUPPLIES TO AID WITH THE CLEAN-UP.  HE AND THE DRIVER SPREAD ABSORBENT ON THE CONCRETE AND STREET TO ABSORB REMAINING RESIDUE. THIS WAS SWEPT UP AND PLACED IN A DRUM.  THEY REMOVED THE GRATE FROM THE STORM DRAIN AND PUMPED ALL LIQUID MATERIAL FROM THE DRAIN SUMP.  THEY WIPED DOWN THE DRAIN WALLS WITH ABSORBENTS TO REMOVE ANY OIL RESIDUE AFTER EMPTYING THE LIQUID MATERIAL.  THE DRAIN CONTAINED SLUDGE IN THE BOTTOM THAT HAD ABSORBED SOME OF THE OIL.  APPROXIMATELY 8 INCHES OF SLUDGE WAS DUG OUT OF THE DRAIN AND PLACED IN A DRUM.  AT THIS POINT IN THE CLEAN UP IT BEGAN TO RAIN.  AOC'S SUPERVISOR POURED ONE BAG OF ABSORBENT INTO THE DRAIN AND MIXED IT WITH THE REMAINING SLUDGE TO ABSORB ANY OIL SHEEN THAT MAY HAVE FLOWED INTO THE DRAIN SUMP WITH THE RAIN.  PER THE SUPERVISOR THIS WAS VERY EFFECTIVE.  AFTER THE RAIN STOPPED, THE ABSORBENT/SLUDGE MIXTURE WAS DUG OUT OF THE DRAIN.  THEY THEN POURED ABSORBENT ON THE STREET AND SWEPT IT UP TO REMOVE RESIDUE.  THIS PROCESS WAS REPEATED.  ALL USED ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS RECOVERED AND PLACED IN A DRUM FOR SHIPMENT TO AOC'S SARALAND FACILITY FOR PETROLEUM RECLAMATION AND DISPOSAL.  AT THIS POINT, THE SITE WAS CLEANED BUT STAINED.  FIVE GALLONS OF MICROBIAL CLEANING AGENT WAS SPRAYED OVER THE SPILL AREA, THE AREA SCRUBBED AND RINSED OFF.  THIS REMOVED THE STAINING.  THE DROP IN LUBE OWNER, DONALD HEBERT, WAS ON-SITE AT THE TIME.  HE IS AWARE OF THE SPILL AND SUBSEQUENT CLEAN-UP.
IMPROPER LOADING CAUSED DAMAGE AND RELEASE OF PRODUCT.

column168: DURING OFFLOAD/SORT OPERATIONS IN OAKLAND, CA.  THIS SHIPMENT APPEARS TO HAVE BEEN DROPPED OR FALLEN FROM A SLIDE.  THE TOP OF THE DRUM WAS DAMAGED ALLOWING APPROX THREE LITERS TO SPILL. WHEN THE CAN WAS UNLOADED THIS PIECE WAS FOUND AT THE BOTTOM.  IT WAS CRUSHED BECAUSE OF THE WEIGHT OF THE OTHER PACKAGES LOADED ON TOP OF IT. THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM THE CUSTOMER WAS CONTACTED AND THE FREIGHT WAS RETURNED.
THIS PACKAGE WAS EMITTING AN ODOR AND WAS OPENED TO FIND 40 BOTTLES OF FINGERNAIL POLISH.  SEVERAL BOTTLES WERE LEAKING.  NO MARKING OR LABELING OR DOCUMENTATION WAS WITH THIS PACKAGE.

A UN SPECIFICATION FIBERBOARD BOX WITH ON MARKINGS OR LABELS OR DOCUMENTATION WAS LEAKING AND EMITTING A VERY STRONG ODOR.  ONE EMPLOYEE HAD THE MATERIAL ON HIS HANDS WITH A BURNING SENSATION.  HE RUSHED TO WASH THEM WITH NO DAMAGE TO HIS HANDS.  HE RETURNED TO WORK.  OTHER WERE VERY SENSITIVE TO THE STRONG ODOR.  THE PACKAGE WAS ALSO EMITTING SMOKE.  AFTER DONNING A RESPIRATOR MASK AND CHEMICAL SUIT THE FEDEX CLEAN-UP SPECIALIST PLACED THE MATERIALS IN TWO STEEL DRUMS.  MSDS AND FURTHER DOCUMENTATION WAS REQUESTED FROM DOW AUTOMOTIVE.  THE FINAL DOCUMENTATION SHOWING THE MATERIAL WAS UN2815 AND CORROSIVE WAS NOT OBTAINED UNTIL THE FOLLOWING DAY. THE FAA WAS CONTACTED FOR INVESTIGATION OF AN UNDECLARED DG PACKAGE.

STEEL DRUM WAS STRUCK BY THE CORNER OF A PALLET FROM ANOTHER SHIPMENT. COLLISION CAUSED A VERY SMALL FRACTURE IN BOTTOM OF THE DRUM ALLOWING APPROX. 3 FL.. OZ. TO LEAK OUT.  ALL ASSOCIATES WORKING WITH SUCH FREIGHT RETRAINED ON PROPER SAFETY TECHNIQUES WHILE DEALING WITH HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCES.

column168: AN IBC OF AMMONIUM HYDROXIDE WAS BEING LOADED ON A VAN TRAILER.  THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR SIDE SHIFTED THE TANK TO POSITION IT FOR PROPER SECUREMENT.  THE OUTLET VALVE PROTECTIVE CAP CAME INTO CONTACT WITH THE SIDE WALL OF THE TRAILER.  THE PRESSURE FROM THE WALL CAUSED THE VALVE TO CRACK WHERE IT CONNECTS TO THE BODY OF THE TANK.  THE LEAKING TANK WAS MOVED TO A TANK TRUCK CONTAINMENT AREA.  THE SPILLAGE WAS PUMPED TO OTHER TANKS AND THE EFFECTED AREA WAS DECONTAMINATED BY RINSING WITH WATER.  THE RINSEAVE WAS RECOVERED FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.

THE UTILITY 5 TRAINMAN WHILE DOING A BRAKE TEST ON TRACK 16 NOTICED THE AMOX 33747 TANK CAR VENTING FROM THE DOME COVER ON TOP OF THE CAR HE IMMEDIATELY CALLED IT IN TO THE YARD OFFICE (ALL RAIL TRAFFIC WAS STOPPED IN THE YARD) WHO CALLED GRS'S CHIEF DISPATCH IN NORTH BILLERICA, MA WHICH IN TURN STARTED THE EMERGENCY CALL PROCEDURE: CHEMTRAC, EAST DEERFIELD FD, SHIPPER (AMERIGAS), AND RAILROAD PERSONAL, BY 0340HRS. THEY WERE ALL NOTIFIED.  WHEN EAST DEERFIELD FD ARRIVED THE TANK CAR WAS STILL VENTING.  0505HRS. FIRE DEPT. HAD APPROVED STARTING YARD BACK UP TO RAIL TRAFFIC, AFTER TAKING AIR SAMPLES.  0645HRS. AMERIGAS TECHNICIAN SHOWED UP NOTICED THE LIQUID LINE DIP TUBE PACKING NUT LOOSE AND TIGHTENING LEVER JAMMED ALSO THE LIQUID LINE TUBE PLUG WAS NOT IN PLACE.  BY 0730HRS. THE TANK CAR HAD BEEN REPAIRED.  2.)  ACTION TO PREVENT FURTHER INCIDENTS WOULD CONSIST OF SHIPPER HAVING A MORE STRICT INSPECTION AND CLOSURE PROCEDURE. FRA TO INSPECT SHIPPER'S FACILITY.

UNLOADING DOCK WORKER NOTICED LEAKING SUBSTANCE ON EXTERIOR OF CARDBOARD PACKAGING.  UPON DISCOVERING THAT THE FREIGHT WAS POISON, THE DSR ALERTED THE SUPERVISOR WHO INSTRUCTED THE DSR TO CONTAIN THE SHIPMENT AND MOVE TO A SAFE AREA.  THE SUPERVISOR THEN ALERTED HIS IMMEDIATE SAFETY SUPERVISOR WHO IN TURN CONTACTED A CONTRACTOR TO CLEAN AND CONTAIN THE SPILL.

TWO (2) OF SIX (6) MANWAY COVER SECUREMENT BOLTS LOOSE, SRIX 80246, JULY 1, 2004, SOUTH EAST DIVISION  AT APPROXIMATELY 1145 HOURS, THURSDAY, JULY 1, 2004 AT PAVONIA YARD IN CAMDEN, NEW JERSEY, A CONRAIL YARD CREW NOTED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM TOP OF TANK CAR SRIX 80246 CONTAINING COMBUSTIBLE LIQUID, N.O.S. WHILE UNDER MOVEMENT.  APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE.  TANK CAR SET OUT OF TRAIN AND ISOLATED.  CONRAIL'S MANAGER RISK MANAGEMENT CONTACTED SHIPPER TO ADVISE OF CONDITION AND HAVE SOMEONE FROM THE SHIPPER EFFECT REPAIR AND MITIGATION OF CAR.  SHIPPER SENT TWO REPRESENTATIVES WHO INSPECTED TANK CAR AND FOUND TWO (2) OF SIX (6) MANWAY COVER SECUREMENT BOLTS NOT ADEQUATELY SECURED.  DURING THE INSPECTION, THE MANWAY COVER GASKET WAS ALSO EXAMINED AND WHILE BEING FOUND IN AN ACCEPTABLE CONDITION, WAS REPLACED IN KIND, NONETHELESS. ALL MANWAY COVER BOLTS WERE RESECURED TOOL TIGHT AS REQUIRED.  KINDER MORGAN PERSONNEL OPENED THE MANWAY COVER TO INSURE THE PRESENCE AND INTEGRITY OF THE MANWAY COVER GASKET, CLOSED AND RESECURED TOOL TIGHT AS REQUIRED.  ON JULY 2, 2004, SHIPPER RETURNED TO YARD AND CLEANED PRODUCT RESIDUE ON SIDES.  TANK CAR CLEARED FOR TRANSPORTATION TO ORIGINAL CONSIGNEE.

AT AROUND 5:00 AM ON JULY 3 WE DISCOVERED ONE BOX THAT WAS DAMAGED BY A PIECE OF WOOD FROM ANOTHER PALLET.  APPARENTLY THE HAZ MAT PLT WAS TRAPPED INSIDE OF A TRAILER AND WHEN THE DOCKMAN WOULD LOAD A PLT INSIDE THIS TRAILER THEY WOULD PUSH UP THE PLT TO MAKE ROOM AND THIS IS PROBABLY HOW THE ONE BOX GOT PIERCED BY THE PIECE OF WOOD FROM ANOTHER PLT.  THE LEAK WAS VERY MINIMAL UNTIL THE DOCKMAN UNLOADED THE PLT FROM THE TRAILER THEN THE PIECE OF WOOD THAT WAS STUCK TO THE BOX FELL OUT THEN IT STARTED TO LEAK A LOT MORE ON THE DOCK.  THE PRODUCT WAS SOME SORT OF PAST SO WE STOPPED THE LEAK BY TURNING OVER THE BOX.  THE SAN BERNARDINO COUNTY FIRE DEPT. HANDLED THE DISPOSAL OF THE PRODUCT.  THIS WAS DAMAGED BY THE SHIPPER.  WE NOTICED IT UPON UNLOADING AT OUR FACILITY.  JEN HANIG

LTCX1809, LOAD ARGON, REFRIGERATED LIQUID, WAS DISCOVERED TO BE VENTING VAPORS FROM THE VALVE BOX AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN SELKIRK, NY. CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SENTINEL INSPECTED THE VALVES AND FOUND THE VAPOR VALVE WAS ICED OVER AND WAS VENTING VAPORS.  FOLLOWING CONSULTATION WITH CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MANAGER, THEY POURED WATER ON THE VALVE TO MELT THE ICE BALL AND CONFIRMED THAT VAPORS WERE LEAKING FROM THE VAPOR VALVE.  THEY CLOSED THE VAPOR VALVE ABOUT 1/4 TURN WHICH STOPPED THE VAPOR LEAK.  THE SHIPPER, PRAXAIR, WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.  PRAXAIR WAS ADVISED OF THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE.

SPECIALIZED PROFESSIONAL SERVICES, INC. (SPSI) WAS CONTACTED FOR ASSISTANCE.  MR. DREW MCCARTHY, SPSI, ADVISED AT 1245, THAT RELEASE WAS DUE TO A MISALIGNED MANWAY COVER GASKET AND ONE OF EIGHT MANWAY COVER SECUREMENT BOLTS NOT BEING TOOL TIGHT.  SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AT 1335 AND ADVISED OF SPSI FINDINGS.  THEY ADVISED AN INTERNAL INVESTIGATION WOULD BE CONDUCTED TO DETERMINE THE ROOT CAUSE AND TAKE MEASURES TO PREVENT FUTURE OCCURRENCES OF THIS TYPE.

A SWITCH CREW REPORTED A TANK CAR, TCDX13265, LOAD SULFURIC ACID, WAS SLOSHING PRODUCT FROM THE TOP WHEN IT WAS MOVED AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN KINGSPORT, TN.  THE YARD MASTER NOTIFIED THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT BECAUSE THE TANK CAR WAS LOCATED WITHIN 100 YARDS OF A CITY PARADE.  CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER, HONEYWELL INTERNATIONAL, VIA CHEMTREC.  HONEYWELL AUTHORIZED CSXT TO RESPOND AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO MAKE NECESSARY REPAIRS TO STOP THE LEAK.  THE CONTRACTOR FOUND THAT THERE WAS A 1/4 IN GAP BETWEEN THE FILL HOLE COVER AND THE LIP OF THE FILL HOLE NEAR THE LIP'S HINGE.  THEY LOOSENED THE THREE SECUREMENT BOLTS WHICH WERE WRENCH TIGHT, REPOSITIONED THE FILL HOLE COVER, AND SECURED THE BOLTS.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED AND WHILE THE CONTRACTOR STOOD BY IT WAS MOVED.  THERE WAS NO SIGN OF LEAKAGE. HONEYWELL WAS ADVISED OF THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE.

CSX TRANSPORTATION RECEIVED A REPORT THAT  A GATX 13283, LOAD COMBUSTIBLE LIQUID NOS, (COAL TAR DISTILLATE), MOVING IN TRAIN Q57715 WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP.  THE CAR WAS SET OUT IN A SIDING IN MISSISSIPPI CITY, MS, MILE POST 000736.21, NEAR THE COURTHOUSE ROAD CROSSING.  CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MANAGER RESPONDED FROM NEW ORLEANS, LA TO MAKE REPAIRS.  THE SHIPPER, ABC COKE, WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.  THE CAR WAS DISCOVERED TO HAVE SLOSHED PRODUCT FROM THE MANWAY BECAUSE THERE NO GASKET INSTALLED IN THE MANWAY COVER.  AN NEW HARD FIBER MANWAY COVER GASKET WAS INSTALLED AND THE MANWAY COVER WAS PROPERLY SECURED.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.  ABC COKE WAS ADVISED OF THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE.

IT WAS ALSO OBSERVED THAT THE CORROSIVE PRODUCT HAD EATEN A HOLE THROUGH THE TRAILER FLOOR.  THE TRAILER FLOOR WAS CLEANED AND ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIAL WAS REMOVED.  TWO 55-GALLON DRUMS OF ABSORBENTS AND TWO 30-GALLON DRUMS OF CONTAMINATED DEBRIS WERE GENERATED FROM THE CLEAN UP.  THE DRUMS WERE PREPARED FOR DISPOSAL.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: IT APPEARS FROM THE CONDITION OF THE FREIGHT THAT THE DRIVER HAD A HARD BRAKE THAT SHIFTED THE LOAD CAUSING BRACING TO FAIL DAMAGING THE DRUMS.  AT DISCOVERY THE RECEIVER CONTAINED THE SPILL THEN TOOK STEPS TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL.  J.B. HUNT IS TAKING PROPER STEPS FOR THE TRAINING OF SAFE DRIVING HABITS FOR THIS DRIVER.
column172: Container, no description given (do not use if at all possible)

column168: DRIVER WAS ON HIS BREAK AT THE PILOT TRUCK STOP & UPON EXITING HIS TRACTOR HE SMELLED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM HIS TRAILER.  UPON INVESTIGATION IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT HAD LEAKED FROM AN AREA AROUND THE TRAILER'S REAR WASHOUT CAP.  TRAILER ONLY LEAKED WHEN IT WAS IN MOTION. NO PRODUCT LEAKED ON THE GROUND.

SWIFT TRANSPORTATION DRIVER DISCOVERED CHEMICAL RELEASING FROM TRAILER AT PETRO TRUCK STOP.  A CLEANUP CONTRACTOR, U.S. ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. WAS DISPATCHED TO PROVIDE CLEANUP AND DECONTAMINATION ACTIONS.  THE CLEANUP CONTRACTOR PERSONNEL TRANSFERRED THE REMAINING CHEMICAL IN THE DAMAGED DRUM TO A EMPTY 55-GALLON DRUM.  SUBSEQUENTLY, THE AREAS OF TRAILER FLOOR & ASPHALT PAVEMENT WERE DECONTAMINATED BY UTILIZATION OF ACID NEUTRALIZER.

UPON DELIVERY, ONE DRUM TO THIS SHIPMENT WAS FOUND LEAKING FROM THE CHIME SEAM.  THERE WAS NO PHYSICAL DAMAGE TO THE DRUM TO CAUSE THE DRUM TO LEAK MAKING THIS A PACKAGE FAILURE.  THE CONSIGNEE ACCEPTED THE LEAKING DRUM AND CLEANED UP THE SPILLED PRODUCT FROM THE TRAILER FLOOR.

column168: DRIVER HAD PULLED OFF ROAD DUE TO BRAKE PROBLEM ON THE TRACTOR.  WHILE DRIVER WAS INSPECTING TRACTOR BRAKE HE NOTICED A VAPOR CLOUD AT REAR OF TRAILER (X312109).  TRAILER WAS LEAKING OUT REAR MANWAY AROUND 5TH/&6TH. BOLT COUNTER CLOCKWISE FROM TOP OF MANWAY.  TRAILER HAD JUST HAD 5YR TESTS TRAILER WAS RETURNED TO BOYD SERVICE AND REPAIRED.  REAR MANWAY GASKET WAS FOUND PINCHED/CRACKED BETWEEN 5TH/6TH BOLT.

column168: FREIGHT NOT SECURED ON THE TAIL END OF TRAILER.  IMPROPER BLOCKING AND BRACING AS THE FREIGHT WAS AGAINST THE TRAILER DOOR.  DSR OPENED THE DOOR AND THE FREIGHT WAS LAYING ON ITS SIDE.
FREIGHT NOT SEALED PROPERLY FROM THE SHIPPER.  VERY LITTLE PRODUCT ON TOP OF THE TOTES.

SPILL WAS DISCOVERED WHEN FREIGHT WAS UNLOADED AND SET AT THE UHO SECTION AT ULA. NO SIGN OF CTNS BEEN DAMAGE OR CRUSHED, CTNS WERE OPENED TO INSPECT FREIGHT, CORROSIVE LIQUID HAD SPILLED BY CAP, CORROSIVE HAD EATEN AWAY THE SEAL AND LIQUID SPILLED OVER THE CAP AND DOWN THE PLASTIC CONTAINER, CARDBOARD BOX CONTAINED THE SPILL.

column168: WHILE SKID WAS BEING LOADED IT CAUGHT JAGGED EDGE OF THE METAL KICK PLATE. THIS RESULTED IN ONE BOX BEING PUNCTURED AND SPILLING.  SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND PRODUCT WAS PUT INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  IT RELABELED AND LOADED BACK ONTO THE TRAILER.

column168: 1. DRUM HAD BEEN RUBBED ON FLOOR AT SHIPPER.  2 CONTINUED TO SEEP OUT OF BOTTOM ROLLED SEED OF DRUM UNTIL REACHING USF DUGAN DOCK HERE IN TUL. column168: DRIVER WAS DELIVERING INTO 1 OF 2 MANIFOLD TANKS.  DRIVER REMOVED CAP FROM 2ND TANK TO STICK TANK TO GET READING.  PRESSURE BUILT UP BETWEEN THE 2 TANKS CAUSING PRODUCT TO COME OUT WHEN CAP WAS REMOVED.  FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AND SPREAD ABSORBENT.  ABSORBENT WAS DRUMMED AND DISPOSED OF BY CLEAN UP CONTRACTOR.

DRIVER WAS MAKING DELIVERY TO UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK WHEN FITTING ON HOSE DISCONNECTED FROM CONNECTION TO TANK WHILE UNLOADING.  SPILL OCCURRED WHEN FITTING POPPED OFF.  DRIVER PUT OUT SPILL PADS AND CONTAINED THE SPILL TO CONCRETE SURFACE.  EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR RESPONDED AND COMPLETED CLEAN UP OF THE AREA AND DISPOSAL OF CONTAMINANTS.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: DRIVER GOT LOADED.  HE DID A SLOSH TEST TO SEE IF ANY PRODUCT WAS LEAKING ANY WHERE FROM THE TRAILER.  HE DID NOT SEE ANY LEAKS.  WHEN HE STARTED TO PULL OFF THE LOADING RACK & SAW SOME PRODUCT COMING OUT OF THE OVERFLOW PIPE FROM THE TOP OF TRAILER.  THE DOME LID GASKET WAS CRIMPED WHEN THE LOADER CLOSED IT.  A NEW GASKET WAS PUT IN.  APPROX. 5 GAL WAS CONTAINED IN THE LOADING RACK AREA.

A SMALL HAZMAT LEAK WAS DISCOVERED ON THE HORIZON PRODUCER AT HATCH #3 STB/SIDE SECOND TIER AFT TANK DCIU810019 WAS LISTED AS AN EMPTY TANK LAST CONTAINING HYDROCHLORIC ACID SOLUTION UN1789.  THE ESTIMATED LEAK OF ONE CUP WAS CONTAINED AND THERE WAS NO PRODUCT THAT ENTERED THE WATER.  THE VESSEL WAS LOCATED 585 MILES FROM THE NEAREST LAND (CAP CANAVERAL).  THE VESSEL NOTIFIED CHEMTREC AND THE U.S. COAST GUARD AT THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER.  THE REPORT NUMBER FOR THE INCIDENT IS 727471.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP BY THE RESPONSE CONTRACTOR IN ELIZABETH, NJ.  THE CAUSE OF THE SPILL WAS SPILLAGE FROM LOADING/UNLOADING REMAINING IN CATCH BASIN AROUND DOME COVER THAT WASN'T CLEANED.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: DELIVERY DRIVER HAD STARTED FILLING THE TANK, TANK WAS AT 47% WHEN A RELIEF VALVE STARTED TO POP OFF.  DRIVER CALLED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT, THEY RESPONDED AND SPRAYED DOWN THE TANK ALL NIGHT LONG INTO THE NEXT DAY. DRIVER TRIED TO PUMP OFF, THAT DID NOT WORK.  DRIVER THEN GOT THE VALVE TO RESEAT, BY THIS TIME TANK WAS AT 26%.  ALL VALVES WERE REPLACED AFTER TANK WAS PUMPED OFF, NO OTHER PROBLEMS.  THE ONLY ROAD CLOSURE WAS TO THE BUSINESS, BUSINESS WAS NOT OPEN AT THE TIME THIS HAPPENED.

WHILE UNLOADING THE INBOUND TRAILER A PALLET OF 10 BAGS (SACKS) WERE UNLOADED.  THEY DISCOVERED A BAG LEAKING AND INVESTIGATED AND FOUND IT TO BE A BAG ON THE BOTTOM THAT WAS PUNCTURED BY A NAIL THAT HAD COME UP IN THE PALLET.  WE GOT WITH THE SHIPPER AND CONSIGNEE TO MAKE THEM AWARE OF WHAT AND HOW THIS HAPPENED.  COPY'S OF THE REPORT HAVE BEEN SENT TO THE ORIGIN TERMINAL AND ALSO DOTHAN GEN OFFICER.

A GFC CARTAGE EMPLOYEE FORKED THIS DRUM WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER.  GFC EMPLOYEES FLIPPED THE DRUM & PLACED UPSIDE DOWN INTO A RECOVERY DRUM.  THEY CLEANED UP WITH "STAY-DRY" AND SWEPT INTO A PLASTIC CAN.  EVERYONE WASHED HANDS & DISPOSED OF GLOVES USED DURING CLEAN-UP.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  DURING A ROUTINE INSPECTION, A LEAK WAS DISCOVERED INSIDE THE TRAILER.  NRC ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES OF LONG BEACH, CALIFORNIA WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP.  THE LOS ANGELES COUNTY FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO OVERSEE THE CLEANUP.  UPON INSPECTION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ONE (1) 5-GALLON PAIL HAD BEEN DAMAGED DUE TO THE LOAD SHIFTING IN TRANSIT.  NRC ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES USED SODA ASH TO NEUTRALIZE THE FREE PRODUCT.  THREE (3) 55-GALLON DRUMS OF NEUTRALIZED PRODUCT, CONTAMINATED PALLETS, AND PPE WERE GENERATED DURING THE CLEANUP.  DISPOSAL WILL BE COORDINATED PER LOCAL, STATE, AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.
column172: Plastic pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE TRAVELING, A LEAK WAS DETECTED COMING FROM THE TRAILER.  THE USF REDDAWAY, INC. VEHICLE PULLED OVER TO THE ROAD SHOULDER TO INSPECT THE FREIGHT.  UPON OPENING TRAILER DOOR, A STRONG ODOR AND FREE LIQUID WERE DISCOVERED INSIDE THE TRAILER.  CALTRANS RESPONDED TO ASSESS THE SITE, ALONG WITH THE CALIFORNIA HIGHWAY PATROL, AND FRESNO COUNTY COMMUNITY HEALTH DEPARTMENT. NRC ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES OF ALAMEDA, CALIFORNIA WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE FREIGHT, ONE 275 GALLON TOTE TANK WAS DISCOVERED DAMAGED.  APPARENTLY, THE TOTE HAD BEEN CRUSHED DURING LOADING. APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS OF FREE LIQUID WERE RELEASED.  NRC ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES PUMPED THE REMAINING FREE LIQUID FROM THE DAMAGED TOTE TANK.  NRC ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES ALSO NEUTRALIZED THE FREE PRODUCT, AND APPLIED ABSORBENTS TO CONTAIN INSIDE THE TRAILER AND ALONG THE ASPHALT ON THE ROAD SHOULDER.  SEVEN (7) 55-GALLON DRUMS OF FREE PRODUCT, THREE (3) 55-GALLON DRUMS OF ABSORBENTS, DEBRIS, NEUTRALIZER, AND PPE, AND ONE CRUSHED TOTE TANK WERE GENERATED DURING THE CLEANUP.  NRC ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES TRANSPORTED THE WASTE TO DK ENVIRONMENTAL FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  THE DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO THE LOCAL HOSPITAL AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE, AND WAS RELEASED WITH NO SYMPTOMS OF EXPOSURES.  ADDITIONAL RESPONSE PLANS DON NOT EXIST AT THIS TIME.

FREIGHT TWAS PALLETIZED.  PALLET WAS LOADED ON TRAILER.  ANOTHER PALLET WAS THEN SLIDE ONTO THE TRAILER.  THE EDGE OF THIS PALLET COLLIDED WITH THE 1ST PALLET.  THE RESULTING COLLISION CAUSED THE EDGE OF THE 2ND PALLET TO PUNCTURE THE BOX CONTINUING THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND CONSEQUENTIALLY 2 OF THE INNER CONTAINERS.

column168: DRIVER PICKED UP AN ORDER WITH 8 DRUMS IN ORDER.  UPON RETURN TO THE FACILITYFLUID WAS LEAKING FROM REAR OF TRAILER.  IT HAD STRATED JUST A FEW FEET BEHIND THE TRAILER. ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, ONE LEAKING ONE HUNDRED POUND STEEL CYLINDER WAS DISCOVERED ON THE DOCK.  THE SPOKANE FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  NRC ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. OF SPOKANE, WASHINGTON WAS ALSO CONTACTED TO ASSIST WITH CLEANUP.  UPON INVESTIGATION OF THE CYLINDER, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT APPROXIMATELY, SEVENTY POUNDS OF FREE PRODUCT RELEASED.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A CRACK IN THE WELD SEAM ON THE BOTTOM OF THE CYLINDER.  THE SPOKANE FIRE DEPARTMENT EVACUATED THE REMAINING PRODUCT FROM THE CYLINDER. NO CLEANUP WAS NECESSARY.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.  ALL STATE AND LOCAL REGULATORY AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: DRIVER WAS MAKING A LEFT TURN AT A CONTROLLED INTERSECTION.  HE HAD JUST STARTED AROUND THE TURN AFTER THE LIGHT TURNED GREEN.  ABOUT HALF WAY THROUGH THE TURN THE SURGE OF THE PRODUCT CAUSED THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER TO ROLLOVER IN THE INTERSECTION.  THE TRAILER WAS ONLY 50% FILLED BECAUSE OF THE WEIGHT PER GALLON OF THE PRODUCT.  AN ADDITIONAL FACTOR IN THE ROLLOVER WAS THE INCLINE OF THE HIGHWAY CAUSED THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER TO LEAN AWAY FROM THE DIRECTION OF THE TURN.  THIS MAGNIFIED THE EFFECT OF THE PRODUCT SURGE.  THE DIVER SIMPLY FAILED TO ANTICIPATE THE CONDITIONS COMING TOGETHER AS THEY DID TO CAUSE THE ROLLOVER.  SPILLED PRODUCT WAS WHAT LEAKED FROM A CLEAN OUT CAP AS THE TRAILER LAID ON ITS SIDE.  THIS WAS COLLECTED, PLACED IN A 55 GALLON DRUM, AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF.

column168: TRACTOR-TRAILER UNIT ARRIVED AT SITE ENTRY SECURITY GATE OF GRAND GULF NUCLEAR POWER PLANT AT PORT GIBSON, MS WHERE A WALK AROUND INSPECTION BY PLANT SECURITY WAS PERFORMED.  THE DRIVER WAS THEN DIRECTED TO MOVE HIS UNIT TO THE NEXT SECURITY CHECK POINT.  WHEN THE UNIT MOVED FORWARD THE SECURITY GUARD DETECTED SULFURIC ACID DRIPPING FROM THE OVERFLOW TUBE COMING FROM THE TANK LOADING DOME AREA.  UPON INVESTIGATION IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE DOME LID HAD NOT BEEN SECURED COMPLETELY TIGHT ALLOWING A SLIGHT SLOSH OF PRODUCT LEAKED FROM THE DOME LID AND ESCAPED VIA THE DOME OVERFLOW TUBE TO THE GROUND.  TOTAL AMOUNT OF SPILLED PRODUCT HAS BEEN ESTIMATED TO BE BETWEEN ONE PINT AND ONE HALF GALLON.  THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS NEUTRALIZED, CLEANED UP, AND DISPOSED OF BY GRAND GULF PERSONNEL.

ON 7/10 AT APPROXIMATELY 1:00 PM EST, COORDINATOR WAS INPUTTING AN ORDER ON BEHALF OF US WASTE.  THIS WAS AN INBOUND ORDER, OFFLOADING THE CONTENTS (46,700 LBS OF SULFURIC ACID) FROM TRACTOR-TRAILER (TRAILER #187) INTO A TANKCAR.  DURING THE INITIAL PROCESSING OF THE ORDER COORDINATOR INADVERTENTLY ASSIGNED ONE RAILCAR (GATX 5923) FOR THE TRANSFER, INSTEAD OF TWO RAILCARS (I.E..:SPLIT LOAD).  THE CONTENTS PREVIOUS CONTAINED INSIDE OF RAILCAR GATX 5923 WERE 179,820 LBS; MAXIMUM CAPACITY PROVIDING SUFFICIENT OUTAGE IS ROUGHLY 200,000 LBS.  COORDINATOR COMPLETED THE ORDER, SHE THEN ISSUED THE DRIVER THE INSPECTION LOADING FORM AND DIRECTIONS TO THE RAILCAR/LOADING AREA.  UPON THE TRACTOR-TRAILER'S ARRIVAL, THE DRIVER ISSUED TRANSLOAD OPERATORS THE INSPECTION LOADING FORM PROMPTING HIM TO UTILIZE RAILCAR GATX 5923.  OPERATORS THEN RADIOED THE OFFICE AND SPOKE WITH COORDINATOR VERIFYING THE RAILCAR NUMBER; TRANSLOAD OPERATOR ALSO ASKED IF RAILCAR GATX 5923 WAS EMPTY.  COORDINATOR ANSWERED "YES".  THE OPERATOR NEVER FURTHER QUESTIONED THE COORDINATOR.  IN ADDITION TRANSLOAD OPERATOR NEVER CONDUCTED A VISUAL CHECK OF THE PREVIOUS QUANTITY CONTAINED INSIDE RAILCAR GATX 5923; A NUT APPLIED TO ONE OF THE MANWAY BOLTS WAS EXTREMELY TIGHT PREVENTING THE MANWAY COVER FROM BEING LIFTED.  TRANSLOAD OPERATOR THEN PROCEEDED TO PREP BOTH TRACTOR-TRAILER (TRAILER #187) & THE RAILCAR (GATX 5923) FOR THE TRANSFER (I.E.: APPLYING FITTING & HOSES).  AT APPROXIMATELY 1:15 PM EST, THE PRODUCT WAS NOTICED SPRAYING OUT OF THE RAILCAR'S AIR INDUCTION PIPE ON GATX 5923.  THE DRIVER THEN IMMEDIATELY DEPRESSURIZED HIS TRUCK LIMITING THE FLOW OF PRODUCT.  CORRECTIVE ACTION: RETRAIN OPERATORS ON THE CRITICAL PROCESS OF OPENING THE MANWAY LID PRIOR TO INITIATING THE TRANSFER PROCESS.  ISSUE TRANSLOAD OPERATOR - A SPIP COUNSELING STATEMENT TO ENSURE THAT THE PROGRESSES FROM THIS INCIDENT ARE CORRECTED AND UNDERSTOOD.  RETRAIN COORDINATORS ON PREPARING SPLIT LOAD DOCUMENTATION.  IN ADDITION COORDINATORS WILL BE EDUCATED ON TANKCAR CAPACITY & PROPER OUTAGES.

column168: SOCI PETROLEUM INC WAS TRANSPORTING 7500 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL FROM THE CENTER TERMINAL IN CLEVELAND, OHIO TO SANTMYER OIL CO., INC, 1055 W OLD LINCOLN WAY, WOOSTER OHIO.  WHILE IN TRANSIT THE BELLY VALVE ON ONE OF THE 2000 GALLON COMPARTMENTS MALFUNCTIONED AND ALLOWED DIESEL FUEL TO DRIP OUT OF THE UNLOADING VALVE.  THE FUEL STARTED TO DRIP OUT OF THE VALVE AFTER THE DRIVER STARTED TO GET TO SR 30 BY PASS AROUND WOOSTER, OHIO.  THE DRIVER EXITED OFF SR 30 TO MAKE HIS DELIVERY TO SANTMYER OIL CO., INC...THE LEAK WAS NOT DETECTED UNTIL DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE SANTMYER OIL CO., INC. UNLOADING AREA.  THE DRIVER MEASURED HIS COMPARTMENT AND DETERMINED BY USING TANK CHART FOR THE TRAILER THAT HE HAD LOST 110 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL.  WHEN THE LEAK WAS DETECTED, THE WOOSTER FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED, CITY OF WOOSTER POLICE DEPARTMENT AND THE STATE HIGHWAY PATROL AND THE EPA.  THE ODOT LOCATED IN WOOSTER WHERE CALLED AND THEY WENT OUT WITH DUMP TRUCK TO SPREAD SAND ALONG EDGE OF SR 30 TO COVER ANY DIESEL FUEL THAT HAD LEAKED OUT OF VALVE.  THE EMPLOYEES OF SANTMYER OIL CO., ALSO WENT TO ALL INTERSECTIONS THAT THE DRIVER STOPPED AT AND SPREAD OIL DRY ON ANY WET SPOTS OF FUEL AND ALSO ON SANTMYER OIL CO., INJC PROPERTY AT THE UNLOADING RACK.  THE CITY OF WOOSTER USED THEIR CURB SWEEPER TO CLEAN UP THE OIL DRY AT THE INTERSECTIONS AND ALL OIL DRY WAS BROOMED AND SHOVELED UP ON SANTMYER OIL PROPERTY.  THE LEAKING BELLY VALVE WAS REPLACED AS WELL THE UNLOADING HEAD AT THE COMPARTMENT THAT WAS LEAKING.

H2O ENVIRONMENTAL GENERATED 300 GALLONS OF NON-HAZARDOUS WASTE AND 694 LBS OF SOLID NON-HAZARDOUS WASTE FROM THE CLEANUP.  COUNSELING AND DISCIPLINARY ACTION FOR DRIVER. APPROXIMATELY TWO-HUNDRED-SIXTY-FIVE GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE BY ADJACENT FREIGHT.  PENCO PACIFIC ENVIRONMENTAL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING TYVEK SUITS, GLOVES, AND ABSORBENT.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND WASTE GENERATED WENT INTO SIX, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON DRUMS.  PENCO PACIFIC ENVIRONMENTAL WILL COORDINATE DISPOSAL.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.  ALL FEDERAL, STATE AND LOCAL REGULATORY AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, ONE CARTON CONTAINING ONE, ONE-HALF GALLON PLASTIC JUG WAS DISCOVERED SATURATED AT THE REAR-QUARTER OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY ONCE CUP OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A LOOSE LID. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES, AMPHOMAG, ABSORBENT PADS, AND BROOMS.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND SATURATED CARTON WERE PLACED INTO ONE, EIGHTEEN GALLON POLY RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE PLASTIC JUG WAS CLEANED, RECOUPED, AND FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, SEVENTEEN, FIVE GALLON PLASTIC PAILS WERE DISCOVERED AT THE HALFWAY POINT OF THE TRAILER.  UPON INVESTIGATION IT WAS DETERMINED THAT SIX PAILS WERE DAMAGED AND ELEVEN WERE UNAFFECTED.  APPROXIMATELY THREE GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO THE LOAD SHIFTING DURING TRANSIT.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING AMPHOMAG, GLOVES, AND ABSORBENT PADS. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND SIX DAMAGED PAILS WERE PLACED INTO ONE, FIVE GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM AND ONE, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM.  THE TWO RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM AND ONE, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM.  THE TWO RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE ELEVEN UNAFFECTED PAILS WERE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

AT 0150 HOURS ON JULY 13TH, CSX TRAIN L54111 DERAILED SEVENTEEN CARS AT MILE POST ANB859 ON THE ATLANTA TERMINAL SUBDIVISION.  TANK CAR GATX90683 (LOAD - SODIUM HYDROXIDE) WAS ONE OF THE CARS INVOLVED IN THE DERAILMENT. THIS CAR CAME TO REST AT APPROXIMATELY THE 160 DEGREE POSITION.  PRODUCT WAS NOTED SLIGHTLY DRIPPING OUT OF THE STUFFING BOX FOR THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  ONCE UPRIGHTED, INVESTIGATION REVEALS THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE TO BE INSUFFICIENT PACKING UNDER THE STUFFING BOX PACKING GLAND NUT.  ADDITIONAL PACKING WAS APPLIED AND CAR SECURED.  APPROXIMATELY TWO GALLONS OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE WAS RELEASED INTO THE BALLAST MEDIA.  THIS WAS NEUTRALIZED ON SITE BY USING ACETIC ACID.

column168: AT 1510 HOURS ON JULY 19TH, CSX YARD CREW Y19119 WAS PULLING OUT OF TRACK A03 WHEN A STRING OF CARS FROM TRACK #6 ROLLED NORTH AND SIDESWIPED THREE CARS BEING SWITCHED BY THE YARD CREW.  AS A RESULT OF THIS COLLISION, TANK CAR UTLX 80688 (LOAD - PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUIFIED) ROLLED OVER ONTO IT'S SIDE.  THE TANK CAR SUSTAINED MINIMUM DAMAGE WITH NO RELEASE OF PRODUCT. THE ROCKY MOUNT FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AND AT 2000 HOURS ISSUED A PRECAUTIONARY EVACUATION OF APPROXIMATELY 25 NEARBY RESIDENTS WHILE THE CAR WAS BEING RERAILED.  THE TANK CAR WAS RERAILED AT 2345 HOURS AND RESIDENTS WERE INFORMED THAT THEY MAY RETURN TO THEIR HOMES.

column168: DRIVER HAD JUST STARTED UNLOADING THE PRODUCT INTO THE CONSIGNEE'S STORAGE TANK WHEN HE NOTICED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE SIDE OF THE CARGO TANK. UNLOADING WAS TERMINATED AND THE AIR PRESSURE USED TO UNLOAD THE PRODUCT WAS BLED OFF.  PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE CARGO TANK WAS CONTAINED AND DISPOSED OF BY CONSIGNEE PERSONNEL.  A TEMPORARY PATCH WAS PLACED ON THE TRAILER THAT THEN ALLOWED THE UNLOADING PROCESS TO CONTINUE.  SUBSEQUENT INVESTIGATION FOUND THE RUBBER LINING OF THE CARGO TANK HAD FAILED.  THE CORROSIVE NATURE OF THE PRODUCT CAUSED A SMALL HOLE  IN THE BARREL OF THE CARGO TANK.  THE TRAILER HAD PASSED A LINING INSPECTION ON 16 APRIL 04.

column168: THE MECHANICAL FOREMAN AT CSC TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN EVANSVILLE, IN REPORTED THAT TANK CAR, FMLX17027, LOAD HYDROGEN PEROXIDE, WAS PLACED ON HIS REPAIR TRACK BECAUSE IT WAS OBSERVED SLOSH PRODUCT FROM THE TOP WHEN MOVED.  THE MECHANICAL FOREMAN ADVISED THAT THE CAR LOOKED LIKE A FIXTURE ON TOP OF THE CAR WAS PARTIALLY DISASSEMBLED.  THE TOP OF THE FIXTURE WAS LYING ON THE TANK AND BOLTS THAT SECURED THE TOP OF THE FLANGE OF THE FIXTURE WERE MISSING.  THE FRANGIBLE DISK WAS INSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE INTACT.  BASED ON THE DESCRIPTION PROVIDED, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE FIXTURE IS THE BREATHING STONE HOUSING.  THE SHIPPER, FMC CORP, WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.  CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT DISCUSSED THE SITUATION WITH FMC AND THEY AGREE IT SOUNDED LIKE THE COVER ON THE BREATHER STONE HOUSING HAD COME LOOSE.  FMC HAD A REPLACEMENT BREATHER STONE ASSEMBLY BROUGHT IN BY TRUCK.  FMC PERSONNEL INSTALLED THE REPLACEMENT ASSEMBLY ON 07/21/2004.  THE CAR WAS SECURED AND RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

column168: GATX91009, LOAD STYRENE M0NOMER, WAS DISCOVERED TO BE DRIPPING PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE (BOV) CAP AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN AVON, IN.  THE SHIPPER, GE PLASTICS, WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.  A REPRESENTATIVE OF ATOFINA FOR GE PLASTICS CALLED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO RESPOND TO REPAIR THE CAUSE THE OF THE LEAK.  THE CONTRACTOR REPORTED THAT PRODUCT WAS LEAKING FROM THE PIPE THREADS AROUND THE TOP OF THE BOV CAP.  THE OPERATING HANDLE FOR THE BOTTOM OPERATED VALVE (BOV) WAS IN THE CLOSED AND SECURED POSITION.  THEY OPENED AND CLOSED THE VALVE A COUPLE OF TIMES TO RESEAT THE VALVE.  PRODUCT WAS DRAINED FROM THE CAP AND IT WAS REMOVED TO CLEAN THE THREADS.  THE CAP WAS INSTALLED AGAIN WRENCH TIGHT.  THE DRIP STOPPED.  WITH THE PRODUCT DRAINED FROM THE BOV CAP, IT IS ESTIMATED THAT 2 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  ATOFINA WAS ADVISED THAT THE WAFER TYPE BOV WAS PROBABLY WAS PROBABLY NOT COMPLETELY SEATED ALLOWING PRODUCT TO LEAK THROUGH.  THE CONTRACTOR RELEASED THE CAR SO THAT IT COULD CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

ON THURSDAY, JULY 22, 2004 AND APPROXIMATELY 23:50, CSX TRAIN CREW J72022 WAS SWITCHING CARS IN THE SIDING IN HENDERSON, KY WHEN TWO TANK CARS DERAILED.  GATX36813, A LOADED TANK CAR OF SULFUR DIXIDE AND NATX 300444, A LOADED TANK CAR OF METHANOL DERAILED AND WERE LEANING AT AN APPROXIMATE 45 DEGREE ANGLE.  ALL APPROPRIATE AGENCY NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE.  UPON ARRIVAL, THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT ORDERED APPROXIMATELY 50 PERSONS EVACUATED FROM THEIR HOMES DUE TO THE DERAILED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS CARS.  A CSX HAZMAT CONTRACTOR RESPONDED ALONG WITH CSX PERSONNEL.  THE CARS WERE RERAILED WITHOUT INCIDENT AND RELEASED FOR SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO PRODUCT WAS LOST FROM EITHER TANK CAR.  THE EVACUATION WAS LIFTED BY THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AT 12:20 ON JULY 23, 2004

column168: AT 1200 HOURS, JULY 13, 2004, ACTX420121, EMPTY TANK WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING IN BOWL, TRACK #20, AT THE TERMINAL RAILROAD ASSOCIATION OF ST LOUIS (TRRA), MADISON, ILLINOIS RAIL YARD.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE TANK CAR HAD RELEASED APPROXIMATELY NINETY (90) GALLONS, EIGHT HUNDRED AND EIGHTY (880) POUNDS OF COAL TAR IN THE AREA.  THE INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO THE STATE OF ILLINOIS, WITH INCIDENT NUMBER H20040983 BEING ASSIGNED.  SINCE THE RQ OF THE PRODUCT EXCEEDED, THE INCIDENT WAS ALSO REPORTED TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER.  SINCE THE SHIPPER WAS LOCATED IN THE AREA AND SERVICED BY THE TRRA, REILLY INDUSTRIES WAS CONTACTED TO RESPOND TO THE INCIDENT.  ON ARRIVAL REILLY INDUSTRIES REPRESENTATIVES NOTIFIED THE TRRA THAT THE ABOVE CAR HAD BEEN UNLOADED AT THEIR FACILITY AND WAS BEING MOVED RESIDUE: LAST CONTAINED TO THEIR LEASED STORAGE TANKS A/C; THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE HANDLE WAS MISSING AND SINCE A VALVE WAS NOT AVAILABLE THE CAR WAS BEING STORED WAITING FOR MATERIALS TO REPAIR.  FURTHER INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT THE PACKING GLAND VALVE WAS MISSING AND WHICH ALLOWED THE STEM TO COME OUT WHICH ALLOWED LEAKAGE OF THE RESIDUE MATERIAL.  IT IS ASSUMED THAT THE STEM BECAME DISPLACED DURING THE SWITCHING OPERATION.  THE MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED TO THE IMMEDIATE AREA AFTER BEING DISCOVERED WITH ESTIMATE DURATION OF LEAK APPROXIMATELY THREE TO FOUR (3-4) HOURS. REMEDIATION OF THE SITE WAS STARTED P.M OF JULY 14, 2004 - COMPLETED P.M. JULY 14, 2004 BY DIG AND HAUL REMEDIATION PROCESS.

column168: DRIVER HAD JUST BEGAN TO UNLOAD THE PRODUCT INTO THE CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK WHEN HE NOTICED THE HOSE CONNECTION AT THE CUSTOMER'S PRODUCT LINE LEAKING.  HE CLOSED THE VALVES TO THE CARGO TANK AND PROCEEDED TO DETERMINE THE POSSIBLE CAUSE OF THE LEAK.  AS HE PLACED HIS HANDS ON THE HOSE FITTING CONNECTED TO THE PRODUCT LINE, THE FITTING BROKE. AFTER GETTING THE PRODUCT ON HIM, THE DRIVER WENT TO THE SAFETY SHOWER TO RINSE THE PRODUCT OFF HIS ANKLE LENGTH CHEMICAL COAT.  THE SHOWER DID NOT WORK.  HE THEN PROCEEDED TO A RESTROOM WHERE HE ATTEMPTED TO FLUSH THE PRODUCT WITH WATER FROM THE SINK.  AFTER A SHORT PERIOD OF TIME A CUSTOMER WORKER TOOK HIM TO ANOTHER SHOWER WHERE HE WAS ABLE TO COMPLETELY RINSE THE PRODUCT OFF.  THE DELAY IN GETTING THE PRODUCT OFF CAUSED THE DRIVER TO SUFFER A MINOR CHEMICAL BURN TO HIS RIGHT ANKLE AND RIGHT HAND.  HE ALSO EXPERIENCED DIFFICULTY BREATHING BECAUSE OF THIS DELAY, PRIMARILY FROM BEING CONFINED ON THE RESTROOM FOR A SHORT PERIOD OF TIME.  THIS CONCERN WAS CAUSE FOR HIM TO BE ADMITTED TO THE HOSPITAL FOR A SHORT TIME PERIOD.  HE WAS RELEASED AFTER TWO DAYS WITH NO COMPLICATION.

FACILITY, A LEAK WAS DISCOVERED COMING FROM ONE (1) INTERMODAL CONTAINER, WHICH CONTAINED SEVENTY-SIX 55-GALLON DRUMS.  AREA WAS ISOLATED, AND THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED.  DOW CHEMICAL COMPANY OF LAPORTE, TEXAS, AND DOW CHEMICAL COMPANY OUT OF TEXAS CITY, TEXAS RESPONDED TO ASSESS THE SITE.  UPON INSPECTION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ONE (1) 55-GALLON DRUM HAD BEEN PUNCTURED DURING LOADING. APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  DOW CHEMICAL COMPANY PERFORMED THE CLEANUP OF THE FREE PRODUCT, AND THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS OVERPACKED.  DOW CHEMICAL COMPANY WILL COORDINATE DISPOSITION OF THE OVERPACK DRUM.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: CARGO TANK EXITED FMCSA VEHICLE INSPECTION AREA AT CAMINO REAL PORT OF ENTRY, WHEN ENTERING TEXAS DOT VEHICLE INSPECTION STATION, INSPECTOR OBSERVED VAPOR GAS LEAKING COMING FROM 1/4 PURGE VALVE ON THE 2" LIQUID DISCHARGE LINE.  INSPECTOR CLOSED PORT TO MOVE CARGO TANK TO A REMOTE AREA. 1/4 INCH PURGE VALVE NUT WAS TIGHTENED AND CARGO TANK WAS ALLOWED TO CONTOUR TRIP, CARGO TANK WAS EMPTY WITH RESIDUE IN CONTAINER.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: SULFURIC ACID TANK CAR WAS BEING BLOWN OVER TO HARCROS STORAGE TANKS.  THE TRANSFER HOSE FAILED APPROXIMATELY ONE HOUR INTO THE TRANSFER PROCESS, WHILE UNDER PRESSURE, CAUSING APPROXIMATELY 1000 GALLONS OF MATERIAL TO SPILL INTO THE PARKING LOT.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: AS DRIVER WAS EXITING LEASE, HE TURNED CORNER TO SHARP AND DROVE TRAILER INTO DITCH CAUSING TRANSPORT TO ROLL OVER.  AS TRAILER ROLLED AND LAYED OVER ON ITS SIDE, AN 8 INCH METAL FENCE POST DAMAGED PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE, VACUUM RELIEF VALVE AND TANK GAUGE ON TOP OF TRAILER CAUSING OIL TO SPILL. APPROXIMATELY 840 GALLONS WAS LOST INTO THE DRY CREEK BED.  DRIVER IMMEDIATELY DIKED AND CONTAINED RELEASE IN DRY CREEK BOTTOM.  A PASSER-BY ASSISTED THE DRIVER IN MAKING COMPANY NOTIFICATIONS WHICH ACTIVATED EMERGENCY SERVICES TO RESPOND TO THE INCIDENT.  VACUUM TRUCKS WERE DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE TO TRANSFER THE REMAINING CONTENTS OF THE TRAILER AND RECOVER FREE PRODUCT IN THE DRY CREEK BED.  REMAINING CONTAMINATION WAS EXCAVATED AND REMEDIATION IS COMPLETE.  THE SITE HAS BEEN RESTORED TO PRE-ACCIDENT CONDITIONS.  WHEN THE TRANSPORT WAS UPRIGHTED, OK DPS INSPECTED THE TRUCK AND TRAILER.  NO DEFECTS WERE FOUND.  ACTIONS TAKEN TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS: DRIVER INVOLVED IN ACCIDENT HAS BEEN DISCIPLINE IN ACCORDANCE WITH COMPANY POLICY.  INCIDENT HAS BEEN THOROUGHLY SHARED WITH ALL COMPANY DRIVERS IN MONTHLY SAFETY MEETINGS EXPLAINING THE CHAIN OF EVENTS, CAUSE, AND CONTRIBUTING FACTORS.  EMPHASIS HAS BEEN PLACED ON LESSONS LEARNED FROM THIS INCIDENT REINFORCING TO ALL TRANSPORT DRIVERS TO ALWAYS BE AWARE OF UNIT POSITIONING ESPECIALLY THE TRAILERS OFF-TRACKING WHILE NEGOTIATING TURNS.

column42: AMMONIA SOLUTION, RELATIVE DENSITY BETWEEN 0.880 AND 0.957 AT 15 DEGREES C IN WATER, WITH MORE THAN 10 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 35 PERCENT AMMONIA
column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  ONE (1) 35,000 GALLON STATIONARY ABOVE GROUND STORAGE TANK AT THE PRAXAIR, INC. MANUFACTURING FACILITY, HAD A FAULTY SAFETY SWITCH, WHICH RESULTED IN THE RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 20,000 GALLONS OF AMMONIA AND WATER SOLUTION. ACCORDING TO LAB RESULTS OBTAINED FROM IOWA TESTING LABORATORIES, INC. OF EAGLE GROVE, IOWA, THE AMMONIA AND WATER SOLUTION CONTAINED 50-57PPM OF AMMONIA.  THE FREE PRODUCT ENTERED A NEARBY STORM DRAIN LOCATED AT THE FACILITY.  THE SHUT OFF VALVE TO THE STORM DRAIN WAS ACTIVATED IMMEDIATELY UPON DISCOVERY OF THE RELEASE.  SAFETY-KLEEN OF DES MOINES, IOWA CONTACTED ENVIRONMENTAL SOLUTIONS, INC. OF OMAHA, NEBRASKA TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. ENVIRONMENTAL SOLUTIONS, INC. PUMPED THE FREE LIQUID FROM THE IMPACTED STORM DRAIN, AND GRAVEL LOT, INTO ONE (1) 20,000 GALLON STORAGE TANK. DISPOSAL WILL BE COORDINATED PER LOCAL, STATE, AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.  ALL FEDERAL, STATE, AND LOCAL REGULATORY AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED OF THE RELEASE.

column168: FREIGHT SHIFTED IN TRUCK DURING TRANSPORT.  PALLET CONTAINING HAZMAT SLID DOWN.  THE SLIDING MOTION CAUSED A LID ON ONE OF THE CONTAINERS TO CATCH ON THE LOAD BAY BAR INTENDED TO HOLD THE SHIPMENT IN PLACE.  THIS PRIED THE LID OPEN ENOUGH THAT A SMALL AMOUNT SPLASHED OUT.

A TANK CAR (GATX 90658) CONTAINING 50% SODIUM HYDROXIDE WAS CONNECTED BY THE UNLOADING LINE TO AN UNLOAD PUMP ADJACENT TO THE RAILROAD TRACK.  THE CAR WAS ON THE SWITCH LIST AS AN EMPTY AND WAS TO BE PULLED FOR RETURN TO VENDOR.  THIS CAR WAS NOT EMPTY.  THE BLUE FLAG HAD BEEN REMOVED BY THE OPERATOR IN CHARGE OF UNLOADING.  THE CN SWITCH CREW CAME IN TO SWITCH THE CARS AND DID NOT NOTICE THAT IT WAS STILL HOOKED UP.  THEY REMOVED THE WHEEL CHOCKS AND COMMENCED TO PULL THE RAILCAR FROM THE UNLOAD SPOT.  THE FLEX HOSE USED FOR UNLOADING SNAPPED AND SODIUM HYDROXIDE SPILLED FROM THE RAILCAR UNTIL THE INNER VALVE WAS CLOSED BY THE OPERATOR IN CHARGE OF UNLOADING.  A NEW OPERATING PROCEDURE WAS WRITTEN WHICH ONLY ADDRESSED SWITCHING ISSUES.  THIS PROCEDURE REEMPHASIZED THE FACT THAT FLAGS AND DERAILS ARE NOT TO BE REMOVED WHILE CARS BEYOND THEM ARE STILL CONNECTED. ALL UNLOADING OPERATORS AND OTHER PERSONNEL INVOLVED WITH SWITCHING OR UNLOADING WILL BE TRAINED ON THIS PROCEDURE.  REFRESHER TRAINING WILL ALSO BE GIVEN COVERING GENERAL TANK CAR LOADING/UNLOADING PROCEDURES.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Abrasion; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: DROP OFF TRAILER FROM DAP AND THE LIQUID WAS ON THE TAIL OF THE TRAILER.  A 55GAL DRUM HAS A HOLE ON THE BOTTOM FROM A NAIL FROM THE PALLET.  DAP IS AN SLC.

THE OPERATOR AT THE PLANT FACILITY WAS IN THE PROCESS OF LOADING SULFURIC ACID AND IN THE PROCESS THE OPERATOR MORE PRODUCT THAN COULD BE LEGALLY TRANSPORTED ON THE HIGHWAY.  THE DRIVER WENT BACK TO THE PLANT FACILITY OFF-LOADING STATION TO REMOVE THE EXCESS PRODUCT.  WHILE OFF-LOADING THE PRODUCT THE PLANT FACILITY OFF-LOADING LINE WHERE A GAUGE WAS ATTACHED TO THE LINE CRACKED AND PRODUCT WAS RELEASED FROM THE AREA WHERE THE GAUGE WAS ATTACHED.  THE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED ON AN IMPERVIOUS SURFACE AND WAS CLEANED UP BY THE PLANT PERSONNEL.  THE LINE AND GAUGE WAS REPAIRED AND NO FURTHER INCIDENTS HAVE OCCURRED.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: ON JULY 1ST 2004 AN EAGLE DRIVER WAS UNLOADING GASOLINE AT THE PANTRY #790 IN MURRELLS INLET, SC.  THE EAGLE DRIVER FAILED TO PROPERLY CONNECT A FITTING AND SPILLED APPROX. 150 GALLONS.  THE SPILLED GASOLINE FLOWED EAST ACROSS THE TANK FILL AREA, ACROSS THE ROAD, AND CONTINUED TO FLOW FOR ANOTHER 210 FEET SOUTH DOWN THE ASPHALT ROADWAY.  EAGLE CONTACTED ACTION ENVIRONMENTAL WHO REQUESTED HERR TO GO TO THE SCENE AND HANDLE CLEAN UP. THE MURRELLS INLET FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE SCDHEC WERE ON SCENE.  THE FIRE DEPT STOPPED THE FLOW OF GASOLINE BY USING OIL DRY AND APPLIED ABSORBENT PADS.  UPON HERR ARRIVAL THE FIRE DEPT LEFT THE SCENE AND HERR CONTINUED APPLYING LOOSE ABSORBENT TO THE GASOLINE.  THE ENTIRE SPILL AREA WAS TREATED WITH F-500 TO INHIBIT GASOLINE VAPORS, REMOVE SHEEN AND TO INITIATE DEGRADATION.  ALL LOOSE ABSORBENT PADS WERE REMOVED WITH NO LIQUID GASOLINE REMAINING.  SCDHEC REP. LARRY WEST GAVE THE OK THAT THE CLEANUP WAS COMPLETE.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: THE DRIVER LOADED PHOSPHORIC ACID AND AFTER LOADING THE DRIVER FAILED TO PROPERLY SECURE THE DOME LID OPENING.  WHEN THE DRIVER PULLED OUT OF THE LOADING STATION THE GUARD NOTICED THAT SOME PRODUCT HAD SPILLED FROM THE CARGO TANK.  THE GUARD IMMEDIATELY STOPPED OUR DRIVER BEFORE EXITING THE PLANT FACILITY.  CTL SENT OUT A CLEAN-UP CREW TO NEUTRALIZE THE SPILLED PRODUCT AND AFTER THE PRODUCT WAS NEUTRALIZED ABSORBENT WAS USE TO CLEAN UP THE NEUTRALIZED PRODUCT.  THE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED TO AN ASPHALT SURFACE. THE DRIVER WAS RE-TRAINED ON PROPER SECUREMENT PROCEDURES AND WAS EVALUATED BY A CERTIFIED DRIVER TRAILER FOR ONE DAY.

column172: General packaging, for type A radioactive materials

column168: TRAILER SPRANG A PINHOLE LEAK.  DRIVER PUT A DRUM UNDERNEATH THE LEAK. CONSIGNEE PLUGGED THE HOLE AND TRANSFERRED THE REST OF THE PRODUCT TO ANOTHER TRAILER.  LOST 1 QUART ON THE GROUND.  50 GALLONS WAS CONTAINED IN THE DRUM.
CAP ON THE DRUM WAS NOT ADEQUATELY SECURED
column172: Drum - fiber, metal or plastic not specified

column168: BNSF TRAIN STOPPED ON MAIN TRACK WITH ETD PROBLEMS & THE CREW ON BNSF LOCAL TRAIN ASSISTING REPORTED OOLU 574164 ON REAR INTERMODAL FLATCAR LEAKING UNKNOWN SUBSTANCE.  FLAGSTAFF F.D. INSPECTED CONTAINER FINDING NO PRODUCT LEAKAGE.  THIS RAILCAR WAS THEN SETOUT AT MAINE, AZ FOR FURTHER INSPECTION. THE FOUR-MEMBER CREW ON THE LOCAL TRAIN ALSO REPORTED PRODUCT INHALATION EXPOSURE & WAS TAKEN TO FLAGSTAFF MEDICAL CENTER FOR EXAMINATION. EMPLOYEES WERE GIVEN OXYGEN, EXAMINED & RELEASED WITH NO FURTHER TREATMENT PRESCRIBED.  ON JULY 7TH, CONTRACT RESPONDERS OPENED OOLU 574164 FINDING TWO 1-GALLON METAL CANS OF TRANS-2-HEXENOL HAD LEAKED AFTER THE BOTTOM CAN SEAMS HAD SPLIT.  ALSO SIX SIMILAR CANS OF A NON-HAZARDOUS COMMODITY SUSTAINED LIKE DAMAGES.  ALL DAMAGED CANS WERE PLACED IN A POLYETHYLENE 55-GALLON OVERPACK DRUM, RETURNED TO THE LOAD AFTER THE SPILLAGE IN OOLU 574164 WAS WIPED CLEAN.

DURING INBOUND TRAIN INSPECTION, PRODUCT ODOR REPORTED EMANATING FROM BLKU 120114 ATOP ENTRAINED FLATCAR & FLATCAR SETOUT OF TRAIN.  FURTHER INSPECTION REVEALED FLANGE BOLTS (BOLTED & WIRED) TO TOP OPERATED OUTLET VALVE NOT SEATED PROPERLY.  WIRE & BOLTS REMOVED, BOLTS RESEATED & TOOL TIGHTENED.  ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR CLEANED SPILLAGE ON TANK CONTAINER & NEUTRALIZED SPILLED PRODUCT ALONG TRACKS IN RAILYARD.

GATX 49428 HAD PRODUCT SPRAY FROM 75 PSI SAFETY RELEASE VALVE (SRV) DURING NORMAL SWITCHING OPERATIONS IN RAILYARD.  A BNSF EMPLOYEE NEARBY WAS LIGHTLY SPLASHED BY SOME PRODUCT & IT WAS WASHED AWAY WITHOUT SKIN INJURY. THE SRV WAS INSPECTED & CLEANED AT THE CONSIGNEE'S FACILITY WITH NO REPORTED DEFECTS.  HYDRAULIC PRESSURE SURGES OF PRODUCT APPARENTLY INITIATED SRV RELEASE.

column168: DURING DERAMP PROCESS, HDMU 451248 REPORTED WITH STICKY PRODUCT DRIP FROM NOSE OF INTERMODAL CONTAINER & IT WAS PLACED INSIDE CONTAINMENT AREA. INVESTIGATION REVEALED 5 JERRICANS HAD LEAKED VIA BUNGS.  HEAVY LADING STACKED ATOP JERRICANS CAUSED PARTIAL CRUSHING & EXPULSION OF ADHESIVE FROM THE BUNG AREA.  ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR OVERPACKED DAMAGED JERRICANS & REMEDIATED SPILLED PRODUCT INSIDE CONTAINER & A SMALL SPLATTER ON THE GROUND.

AFTERWARDS, UTLX 74967 SPOTTED AT CONSIGNEE'S FACILITY FOR UNLOADING.  CONSIGNEE REPORTEDLY CALLED SHIPPER TO NOTIFY THEM OF THIS INCIDENT.

THIS DEFICIENCY WAS CORRECTED RESULTING IN A GOOD SEAL & MANWAY SECURED.  ALTHOUGH NO ACTIVE RELEASE DISCOVERED AT THIS TIME, IT WAS ESTIMATED THAT POSSIBLY 50 TO 100 GALLONS OF PRODUCT ESCAPED ENROUTE. CONSIGNEE NOTIFIED & REQUESTED TO CLEAN PRODUCT RESIDUE FROM TANK SHELL AFTER UNLOADING.

ON JUNE 25 2004 A SHIPMENT OF PCB TRANSFORMERS WERE PICKED UP AT ONYX ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, FLANDERS NJ BY FREEHOLD CARTAGE.  THE TRANSFORMERS WERE SHIPPED AS IS, IN ACCORDANCE WITH SPECIAL PROVISION 81 OF 49 CFR 172.102.  TWO OF THE TRANSFORMERS WERE EQUIPPED WITH SIDE MOUNTED INSULATING BUSHINGS.  IN ORDER TO PROTECT THE BUSHINGS FROM BEING HIT BY A FORKLIFT OR A PERSON WALKING PAST THE CONTAINER, THE TWO TRANSFORMERS WERE STRAPPED TO A PALLET WITH THE BUSHING POINTED TO THE MIDDLE.  ALTHOUGH THIS PREVENTED THE BUSHING FROM BEING STRUCK BY A FORKLIFT OR OTHER ITEM, THE BUSHINGS RUBBED AGAINST EACH OTHER DURING TRANSPORT AND BECAME LOSE.  THE SHIPMENT ARRIVED AT OUR PORT WASHINGTON FACILITY ON JULY 14, 2004. MATERIALS WERE BEING TRANSFERRED TO AN ONYX ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES TRAILER TO CONTINUE ON TO THEIR FINAL DESTINATION.  WHILE DOING THE TRANSFER OF THESE TRANSFORMERS, WE DISCOVERED THAT THEY WERE LEAKING.  THE TRAILER WAS EQUIPPED WITH A STEEL FLOOR AND SECONDARY CONTAINMENT SYSTEM AND NO MATERIALS WERE SPILLED OUTSIDE THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY ONE PINT OF MATERIAL TOTAL WAS RELEASED FROM THE TRANSFORMERS.  THE TRAILER WAS CLEANED UP IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE US EPA REQUIREMENTS FOR DECONTAMINATION OF PCB SPILLS.  THE TRANSFORMERS WERE PACKAGED INTO LARGER CONTAINERS AND THE CLEAN UP DEBRIS WAS CONTAINERIZED, ADDED TO THE MANIFEST AND SHIPPED TO THE FINAL DESTINATION FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY REPORTED TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER, WISCONSIN SERC AND OZAUKEE COUNTY LEPC AND A WRITTEN REPORT HAS BEEN SUBMITTED TO THE WISCONSIN DNR.

DRIVER OF COMPANY VEHICLE CARRYING SODIUM HYDROXIDE & SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE WAS TRAVELING AT A SPEED OF 42 MPH, TRAFFIC IN FRONT OF HIM HAD STOPPED SUDDENLY AND THE DRIVER WAS UNABLE TO GET STOPPED IN TIME CAUSING A COLLISION WITH THE VEHICLE IN FRONT OF HIM.  THE IMPACT OF THE COLLISION CAUSED THE CHEMICAL TANKS TO SHIFT FORWARD BREAKING THE FITTINGS ON THE VALVES.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS DISPATCHED IMMEDIATELY AND BEGAN TO RESPOND TO THE SPILL.  HEATER UTILITIES IMMEDIATELY CALLED A LOCAL EMERGENCY ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP COMPANY (HEPACO) FOR THE CLEANUP OF THE SPILL.  THEIR CLEANUP CREW WERE ON THE SCENE WITHIN AN HOUR TO RESPOND TO THE SPILL.  TO PREVENT ANY FUTURE INCIDENTS, THE COMPANY HAS REMINDED THE EMPLOYEE OF THE IMPORTANCE OF HAVING A SAFE FOLLOWING DISTANCE WHILE CARRYING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  ALL EMPLOYEES WILL RECEIVE ADDITIONAL TRAINING ON PREVENTING THIS TYPE IF INCIDENT IN THE FUTURE.  THE COMPANY HAS ALSO EVALUATED THE CURRENT CARGO AREA USED FOR TRANSPORTING CHEMICALS TO SEE IF ANY MODIFICATIONS CAN BE MADE AND AT THIS TIME IT HAS BEEN DETERMINED THAT THE CURRENT SYSTEM USED IS COMPLETELY ADEQUATE.

column168: A SWITCH CREW WORKING IN CSX TRANSPORTATION'S HOWEL YARD IN EVANSVILLE, IN, REPORTED AN ODOR COMING FROM A SHPX301882, RESIDUE LAST CONTAINED, ETHANOL. THE GENERAL CAR FOREMAN FOR THE MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT WHO IS ALSO A CSXT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SENTINEL INSPECTED THE CAR AND REPORTED THAT IT WAS DRIPPING PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE (BOV).  THE OPERATING HANDLE FOR THE BOTTOM OPERATED BOV WAS NOT SECURE AND WAS HANGING DOWN IN THE OPEN POSITION.  HE OBSERVED THAT THE SECUREMENT PIN FOR THE OPERATING HAND WAS HANGING FROM ITS SECUREMENT CHAIN.  HE RAISED THE OPERATING HANDLE TO THE CLOSED POSITION AND SECURED IT WITH THE PIN.  THE LEAK FROM THE BOV SLOWED TO A DRIP.  HE THEN ATTEMPTED TO LOOSEN THE BOV CAP PLUG TO DRAIN PRODUCT ENTRAINED IN THE BOV PIPE.  THEN HE PUT THE WRENCH ON THE PLUG, THE BOV CAP FELL OFF!  HE INSTALLED THE BOV CAP PROPERLY AND MADE IT WRENCH TIGHT.  THE LEAK WAS STOPPED.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.  THE SHIPPER, CHEMEX, AND THE CONSIGNEE, GRAIN PROCESSING WERE NOTIFIED THROUGH CHEMTREC.  CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT DISCUSSED THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE WITH BOTH THE SHIPPER AND THE CONSIGNEE.

column168: PSC CONTRACTED TO TRANSPORT HYDROCHLORIC ACID IN PLEASANTON, TEXAS AND WAS TO DELIVER PARTIAL LOADS TO FACILITIES IN WACO AND MOUNT PLEASANT, TX.  THE SHIPPER OWNED THE FACILITY OF ORIGIN AND BOTH DESTINATION FACILITIES. UNLOADING DELAYS IN WACO DID NOT ALLOW FOR THE MOUNT PLEASANT DELIVERY TO BE MADE THE SAME DAY.  THEREFORE, A STAY IN SUPER 8 MOTEL IN MOUNT PLEASANT WAS REQUIRED.  AT APPROXIMATELY 5:00 AM, OF JULY 29, 2004, THE LEAK WAS DISCOVERED BY MOUNT PLEASANT POLICE DEPARTMENT.  UPON DETECTION OF THE SPILL ALL APPROPRIATE FEDERAL, STATE AND LOCAL AGENCIES WERE CONTACTED AND THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND AFFECTED AREA DECONTAMINATED.  THE REMAINING PRODUCT WAS LOADED ONTO ANOTHER CARGO TANKER AND DELIVERED TO THE MOUNT PLEASANT FACILITY.  AFTERWARDS, THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER WERE REMOVED TO A SAFE HARBOR.  THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK IS A FAILED WELD/SEAM ON A "BELL REDUCER" COUPLING AT THE VALVE.  THE CAUSE OF THAT FAILURE IS STILL UNDER INVESTIGATION, BUT IT IS BELIEVED THAT THE VALVE WAS DEFECTIVE IN A WAY, WHICH WENT UNDETECTED.  THE TRACTOR AND TANKER WILL REMAIN OUT OF SERVICE UNTIL REPAIRED, INSPECTED AND DETERMINED TO BE SAFE FOR USE.  AS A PRECAUTION ONLY, THE DRIVER WILL BE RETRAINED IN MOTOR CARRIER SAFETY REGULATIONS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  NOTE FOR SECTION # 24 PSC WOULD LIKE FOR USDOT TO BE AWARE OF THE REASONING FOR MARKING "VAPOR (GAS) DISPERSION."  THE PRODUCT WAS VAPORIZING DUE TO THE HUMIDITY AND RAIN AT THE TIME OF THE SPILL, AS OPPOSED TO A LEAK OF GASEOUS CARGO.

column168: RAIL CAR WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING WHILE IN NORFOLK SOUTHERN'S RAIL YARD IN SHEFFIELD, AL.  THE RAILROAD CALLED IN AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR TO ASSIST IN THE RESPONSE.  UPON ASSESSING THE SITUATION, IT WAS INDICATED THAT THE DISC ASSEMBLY ON THE RAIL CAR'S RELIEF VALVE WAS JAMMED OPEN, ALLOWING AMMONIA VAPOR TO ESCAPE.  THE RAIL CAR REQUIRED DEGASSING BEFORE A REPAIR COULD BE MADE.  TANNER INDUSTRIES HAD BEEN NOTIFIED OF THE LEAK, AS THE CAR HAD SHIPPED FROM OUT FACILITY.  WE DISPATCHED A DRIVER TO THE SITE TO DEGAS THE CAR FOR REPAIR.  ONCE THE DEGAS WAS COMPLETE THE RELIEF VALVE WAS REPLACED AND THE CAR RELEASED.  NORFOLK SOUTHERN PERSONNEL VERBALLY INDICATED THAT THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES DUE TO THE LEAK.

UTLX 99545 NOTED BY CARRIER PERSONNEL WITH PRODUCT ODOR IN AREA OF CAR. CAR ISOLATED AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED.  SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES, HEPACO, INC., RESPONDED AND REPLACED A DEFECTIVE "O" RING IN THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE STOPPING THE RELEASE.

GPPX 9120 WAS NOTED VENTING INSIDE CONSIGNEE FACILITY.  CAR ISOLATED AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED.  SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES, JBR ENVIRONMENTAL, RESPONDED AND DISCOVERED MATERIAL WAS REACTING DUE TO ELEVATED TEMPERATURE RESULTING IN PRESSURE BUILD-UP.  PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE WAS FUNCTIONING AS DESIGNED. CONTRACTOR OFF-LOADED ONE ROLL-OFF CONTAINER OF MATERIAL.  POLYMERIZATION PROCESS STOPPED ON 8-2-04.  CAR MOVED TO SPARTANBURG, SC, UNDER FRA MOVEMENT AUTHORITY FOR PRODUCT REMOVAL AND DISPOSAL.

DRIVER LEFT THE HIGHWAY ONTO THE SHOULDER OF THE ROAD.  SINCE THE SHOULDER WAS EXTREMELY WET AND SOFT, HE COULD NOT TURN HIS TRUCK BACK ONTO THE HIGHWAY.  HE CAME TO A COMPLETE STOP ON THE SHOULDER.  THE TRUCK SANK IN THE SOFT GROUND AND TURNED OVER DOWN ROLLING DOWN A HILL.  THE TANK DID NOT FAIL.  HOWEVER, IN THE PROCESS OF PUMPING THE #6 FUEL OIL INTO ANOTHER TANK, 3 GALLONS WAS SPILLED.  ALSO, WHEN THE TRUCK WAS BEING PULLED BY A WRECKER, A DIESEL LINE FROM THE ENGINE WAS BROKEN AND 7 GALLONS OF DIESEL WAS SPILLED BEFORE THE LEAK WAS STOPPED.  THE INCIDENT WAS REPORTED EARLIER TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER IN CASE A REPORTABLE QUANTITY WERE TO SPILL (BUT THIS DID NOT HAPPEN).  THE SOIL AROUND THE 3 GALLONS OF #6 AND 7 GALLONS OF DIESEL WAS EXCAVATED AND DISPOSED OF AT A LICENSED SITE.  THE WESTBOUND LANES OF US 460 WERE CLOSED FOR FIVE HOURS WHILE THE TRUCK WAS PULLED UP THE HILL.  TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS, WE WILL INCREASE TRAINING ABOUT THE IMPORTANCE OF NOT LEAVING THE HIGHWAY.

WE WERE IN THE PROCESS OF TRANSFERRING THE ALKYD RESIN FROM OUR TANK TRAILER TO THE CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK.  THE PRODUCT WAS BEING PUMPED THROUGH HOSES THAT WERE CONNECTED TO THE CUSTOMER'S INLET FROM OUR TANK TRAILER.  THE FAILURE OCCURRED WHEN A SPLICED SECTION OF THE HOSE CAME APART RELEASING THE HOT RESIN.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF THE PUMP, HOWEVER, BEFORE DOING SO APPROXIMATELY 200 GALLONS OF RESIN WAS RELEASED ONTO THE PAVEMENT.  THE DRIVER AND PLANT PERSONNEL CONTAINED THE PRODUCT WITH SAND AND ABSORBENT PILLOWS.  IN ADDITION THEY WORKED WITH SHOVELS TO REMOVE THE PRODUCT FROM THE PAVEMENT, UNTIL THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR ARRIVED TO CLEAN UP THE PRODUCT THOROUGHLY.

A TEAM OF RESPONDERS WERE DISPATCHED FROM THE GEISMAR FACILITY TO GO CAP THE FLANGE AND OFF LOAD THE TRAILER.  THE PRODUCT WAS SUCCESSFULLY OFF LOADED, PRESSURE RELIEVED OFF TRAILER AND RETURNED FOR REPAIRS.  TRAILER WAS REPAIRED, TESTED, AND PLACED BACK INTO SERVICE.  THE GEISMAR MAINTENANCE GROUP ARE CONDUCTING AN INCIDENT INVESTIGATION TO DETERMINE THE ROOT CAUSE.

column168: SHIPMENT ARRIVED, DRIVER NOTICED SMELL AND A SHIFTED LOAD.  -DECIDED TO HANDLE AS SPILL INCIDENT, GOT PERSONS WITH SAFETY GEAR TO ENTER TRAILER.  - MOVED CARTONS TO ANOTHER PALLET FOR REMOVAL FROM TRAILER.  -MOVED PALLET TO LARGE VENTILATED HOOD FOR RE-PACKAGING.  -REPACKAGED AND DISPOSED CONTAMINATED PACKAGING MATERIALS.  RECOMMENDATIONS: -TORQUE CLOSURES TO RECOMMEND LIMIT PRIOR TO SHIPMENT.  -SECURE LOAD WITH SHRINKWRAP AND BANDING TO UNITIZE LOAD.  WE RECEIVED A SHIPMENT OF TRIFLUOROACETIC ANHYDRIDE WHICH LEAKED DURING SHIPMENT.  IT APPEARS THAT THE LEAKAGE OCCURRED WHEN CARTONS (6 OF 31) ON THE TOP ROW FELL OVER DURING TRANSIT FROM THE LOCAL ROADWAY TERMINAL (ONLY 1 OF 3 METAL BANDS WERE SECURING THE CARTONS TO THE PALLET, NO SHRINK WRAP OR OTHER METHOD WAS PRESENT TO UNITIZE THE LOAD).  THREE OF THESE SIX CONTAINERS LEAKED TRIFLUROACETIC ANHYDRIDE INTO THEIR CARTONS AND THE SURROUNDING CARTONS. WHEN THE TRUCK ARRIVED A STRONG ORDER OF TRIFLUOROACETIC ANHYDRIDE WAS PRESENT WHEN THE TRAILER DOOR WAS OPENED.  AT THIS POINT WE DECIDED TO HANDLE THIS AS A HAZARDOUS SPILL INCIDENT.  THE PICTURES ATTACHED SHOW PROMEGA BIOSCIENCES EMPLOYEES EQUIPPED WITH BREATHING AIR.  THEY ACCESSED THE SITUATION THEN REMOVED THE MATERIAL TO LARGE PRODUCTION HOODS FOR RE-PACKAGING.

column168: OPERATOR REMOVED THE PLUG FROM THE "A" SIDE LIQUID VALVE ON THE RAIL CAR AND SOME AMMONIA VAPOR CAME OUT.  HE CHECKED THE VALVE TO MAKE SURE IT WAS CLOSED, AND THE LEAK CONTINUED.  HE REPLACED THE PLUG BACK IN THE "A" SIDE VALVE AND CONTACTED THE CORPORATE OFFICE.  OPERATOR WAS INSTRUCTED TO OFFLOAD THE RAIL CAR FROM THE "B" SIDE LIQUID VALVE.  ONE CAR EMPTIED, IT WILL BE DEGASSED AND A MOBILE CREW BROUGHT IN FOR REPAIR.  THERE WERE NO OFF-SITE COMPLAINTS OF AMMONIA ODOR, NO EVACUATIONS WERE MADE, AND NO INJURIES REPORTED.  LESS THAN 5 POUNDS OF PRODUCT WAS ESTIMATED TO HAVE BEEN RELEASED.

DURING LOADING ONTO THE OUTBOUND TRAILER, ONE DRUM WAS STRUCK WITH A FORK AND PUNCTURED.  IT LEAKED ABOUT THREE GALLONS OF CONTENTS BEFORE DOCK PERSONNEL TURNED IT ONTO ITS SIDE.  THEY CLEANED UP THE SPILLAGE WITH OIL DRY.  THEY BAGGED THE OIL DRY AND PUT IT INTO A SALVAGE DRUM ALONG WITH THE DAMAGED DRUM.

A TWO DRUM SHIPMENT HAD BEEN STAGED IN A RACK ON THE DOCK.  A DOCK WORKER OBSERVED LEAKAGE FROM ONE OF THE DRUMS.  INSPECTION OF THE DRUM REVEALED A SMALL TEAR IN ITS BOTTOM.  THE DRUM HAD BEEN FORKED.  DOCK PERSONNEL PUT THE DRUM INTO A 95 GALLON OVERPACK AND HELD IT IN OS&D TO AWAIT INSTRUCTION FROM THE SHIPPER.  SPILLED MATERIAL WAS NEUTRALIZED, CLEANED UP AND PACKED INTO A DRUM.

DURING STRIPPING OF AN INBOUND SHUTTLE THE UNLOADER FOUND A NUMBER OF PAILS CRUSHED.  SOME HEAVY FREIGHT HAD BEEN LOADED ON TOP OF THEM.  THREE OF THE PAILS WERE LEAKING.  DOCK PERSONNEL REMOVED THE LEAKING PAILS AND SOME OTHERS THAT WERE BADLY CRUSHED, FOR A TOTAL OF TEN PAILS.  THEY CLEANED THE TRAILER FLOOR WITH OIL DRY.  THE DAMAGED PAILS WERE PUT INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND HELD IN OS&D.  THE CLEAN UP MATERIALS WERE PUT INTO ANOTHER DRUM AND HELD FOR DISPOSAL.

THIS SHIPMENT OF CYLINDERS ON PALLETS HAD BEEN DOUBLE STACKED.  ANOTHER PALLET HAD BEEN LOADED ON TOP OF THE CYLINDERS.  DURING TRANSIT, THE BOTTOM PALLET FAILED.  THE VALVES ON TWO OF THE CYLINDERS BROKE OFF, RESULTING IN THE ESCAPE OF THEIR ENTIRE CONTENTS.  ALL OF THE GAS HAD DISSIPATED BY THE TIME THE DALLAS LOCAL DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE CONSIGNEE.  THE CONSIGNEE ACCEPTED THE ENTIRE SHIPMENT WITH A NOTATION OF ITS CONDITION.

column168: HTS WAS CONTRACTED BY A THIRD PARTY, (U.S. FILTER) WHO REQUESTED A STAINLESS STEEL TANKER, CREATED THE PAPERWORK, AND PROFILED THE WASTE FROM CASPIAN.  SEE ATTACHMENT FOR THE SEQUENCE OF EVENTS.  TO PREVENT THIS FROM HAPPENING AGAIN HTS WILL REQUIRE COPIES OF ANY ANALYTICAL AND/OR SAMPLE PRIOR TO ANY BULK SHIPMENT.  REPORTED TO WORK AT 0700 - HOOKED UP TRACTOR 341 TO SS TRL.  016 - PRE-TRIPED - PUT ON 5 LOADING 2" CHEMICAL HOSE AS REQUESTED - CHECKED TO MAKE SURE I HAD SS FITTINGS - MISSING 3-2 SS FITTING.  TOLD KIRT AND WE LOOK AROUND AND COULDN'T FIND ONE - CALLED AROUND TO FIND ONE - I WENT TO HOSE MAN TO PICK ONE UP AT 0800 - THEY DIDN'T HAVE ONE SO CALLED IN AT 0900 AND KIRT HAD FOUND ONE AND WOULD BE IN YARD AT 1000.  WENT BACK TO YARD AND WAITED FOR FITTING TO ARRIVE - IN YARD USED TRA 335 DROPPED MUD TANK IN WASH RACK - HOOKED UP TO AN 21,000 CROWN TANK FOR ANOTHER DRIVER TO DEL. LATER.  3-2 SS FITTING ARRIVED AND I LEFT FOR SAN DIATO AT 1030.  ARRIVED ON SITE AT 1245, CASPIAN INC 4957 RUFFIN RD. AN WORKER AT CASPIAN SAW ME AND DIRECTED ME TO FOLLOW HIM IN HIS CAR TO SITE: WAS DIRECTED TO LOADING SITE.  CALLED DISPATH AT 1300 LET THEM KNOW I WAS ON SITE. WAS TOLD THEY WERE NOT QUITE READY - SO DID PAPER WORK. THEY HAD THERE OWN HOSE AND PUMP SET UP.  STARTED LOADING AT ABOUT 1330. WE LOADED THROUGH REAR DOME OF TRAILER FROM TANK INSIDE BUILDING.  I PUT HOSE INTO READ DOME - TANK WAS EMPTY & CLEAN.  I TIED HOSE TO TANK AND THEY STARTED PUMPING.  LIQUID WAS RUSTY BROWN COLOR.  WHILE LOADING I FELT TANK AND IT DID NOT GET HOT - ONLY WARM TO TO TRUCK.  USING AN AIR PUMP IT PULSE'S AND YOU COULD SEE RED VAPORS AT DIFFERENT TIMES FROM DOME.  THE TWO MEN LOADING ME WERE MANING THE HOSE AND PUMP.  AFTER EMPTYING TANK FROM INSIDE BUILDING THEY MOVED POLY TOTE BINS FROM OUTSIDE TO INSIDE BUILDING IN SHADE AND WHERE HOSE WERE.  ABOUT 1500 PUMPED OUT OF TOTE BINS.  ABOUT AFTER 3/4 OF 1ST TOTE WAS PUMPED GOT CLOGGED UP AND THEY CHANTED AIR PUMPS. - CONTINUED TO PUMP OUT REMAINING OF 1ST TOTE AND THEN PUMPED OUT 4 MORE TOTE BINS.  THE LIQUID WAS THE SAME COLOR AS TANK INSIDE OF THE FIRST TOTE BIN AS I REPOSITIONED THE HOSE IN TANK SO IT WOULD NOT BE IN LIQ SO IT WOULDN'T BE A MESS WHEN WE WERE FINISHED SO HOSE WOULDN'T BE DRIPPING WHEN REMOVED.  WHEN FINISHED WITH TOTE BINS THEY PUMPED AND SMALL AMOUNT OF WATER TO CLEAR HOSE.  I REMOVED HOSE FROM TRAILER AND TIGHTEN DOME LID DOWN - LIQUID WAS RUSTY BROWN IN COLOR.  FELT TANK AND WAS ONLY WARM AND TANKER WAS IN SUNLITE ALL AFTERNOON TEMP.  IN MID 80'S.  MOVE TRA-TRL OUT OF THAT POSITION TO MAKE ROOM FOR ANOTHER TRUCK TO GET IN TO PICK UP ROLL OFF BINS. CHECKED LIQ LEVEL AND AIR WEIGHT OVAGE.  WEIGHT WAS OK AND TANK HAD APP. 3200 GALS IN IT.  OWNER OR BOSS SIGNED MANIFEST & LAND BAND FORM.  GAVE HIM COPIES AND ONE OF THE MEN WHO LOADED ME GAVE ME AN CHECK FOR US FILTERS. CALLED HTS & TOLD THEM I WAS LOADED AND LEAVING.  PLACARD LOAD AND LEFT AT 1630.  TRAVELED NORTH ON RUFFN TO C52 EAST BOUND RAMP.  CON

column168: ON JULY 17, 2004, THE DRIVER WAS EASTBOUND ON INTERSTATE 40 DRIVING APPROXIMATELY 45-50 MPH WHEN HE APPROACHED A FUNERAL PROCESSION.  AS THE TRAFFIC WAS SLOWING A VEHICLE MOVED INTO THE DRIVERS LANE OF TRAVEL, WHICH CAUSED THE DRIVER TO TAKE EVASIVE ACTION AND THE TRUCK AND TRAILER LEFT THE HIGHWAY.  THE SUDDEN MOVEMENT CAUSED THE TRAILER TO ROLL AND COME TO A REST ON ITS TOP SIDE IN THE CENTER MEDIAN.  THE TRAILER DID NOT FAIL DURING THE ACCIDENT.  THE SPILLAGE OCCURRED WHEN THE TRAILER WAS UPRIGHTED AND THE HOLES THAT WERE DRILLED TO REMOVE THE FUEL WERE NOT PLUGGED.

column168: ON JULY 9TH, 2004, A LOADED ANHYDROUS TANK CAR WAS DELIVERED BY THE UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD TO THE RECEIVING TRACK IN BENSON, ARIZONA.  NOTIFICATION THAT THE CAR WAS VENTING WAS GIVEN TO THE BENSON POLICE DEPARTMENT BY A UNION PACIFIC EMPLOYEE ON JULY 11TH.  INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT A PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE WOULD NOT RESET, CAUSING CONTINNAL VENTING OF GAS FROM THE CAR.  NO VISIBLE LIQUID SPILLAGE OCCURRED, NO INJURIES WERE SUSTAINED AND THERE WAS NO CONTAMINATION OF ANY KIND.  THE REMAINING ANHYDROUS AMMONIA WAS TRANSPORTED TO AND UNLOADED AT APACHE NITROGEN PLANT WITHOUT INCIDENT.

WE AT TEXOMA AG PRODUCTS WERE NOTIFIED BY THE WTJ RAILROAD THAT AN ANHYDROUS AMMONIA (NH3) CAR (GATX 95817) EN ROUTE TO OUR FACILITY WAS LEAKING AT THEIR PICK UP SITE IN FREDERICK, OK.  (APPROX 45 MILES NW OF BURKBURNETT)  UPON ARRIVAL AT OUR FACILITY WE DISCOVERED THAT A GASKET WAS LEAKING ON THE LIQUID VALVE OF THE CAR.  OUR HAZMAT CERTIFIED EMPLOYEE WAS ABLE TO RELIEVE THE PRESSURE, THUS ELIMINATING THE LEAK, BY TRANSFERRING THE ANHYDROUS AMMONIA TO OUR STORAGE FACILITY.  AFTER COMPLETION OF THE TRANSFER THE CAR WAS WEIGHED TO OBTAIN THE AMOUNT OF PRODUCT LOST.  IT WAS THEN RELEASED BACK TO THE SHIPPER (KOCH NITROGEN) FOR IMMEDIATE REPAIR.

UPON ARRIVAL AT THE TERMINAL, A TRUCK DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED TO OFFLOAD HIS TANK TRUCK OF FERROUS CHLORIDE INTO RAILCAR UTLX 11211.  THIS RAILCAR WAS ALREADY FULL OF PRODUCT BUT THIS FACT WAS MISSED DUE TO A CLERICAL ERROR. UPON THE START OF DISCHARGE INTO THE CAR THE RAILCAR OVERFLOWED THROUGH THE AIR INLET LINE.  THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO CLOSE A VALVE ON THE INLET LINE BUT LEFT OPEN THE LIQUID DISCHARGE VALVE.  AT THE TIME THE CAR WAS BEING FILLED THROUGH THE VALVE AND STANDPIPE OF THE RAILCAR.  THE DRIVER DESCENDED FROM THE CAR AND DISCONNECTED THE PRODUCT HOSE FROM THE REAR OF THE TANK TRAILER, ALLOWING PRODUCT FROM THE RAILCAR TO FLOW THROUGH THE HOSE AND ONTO THE GROUND.  AN OPERATOR THEN ACCESSED THE LIQUID VALVE TO CLOSE IT AND SHUT OFF THE FLOW OF PRODUCT.  ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS USED TO CONTAIN THE SPILLED MATERIAL AND PREVENT MOVEMENT OF THE SPILLAGE.  AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTED WAS CALLED TO FURTHER CONTAIN THE MATERIAL AND TAKE UP ALL OF THE SPILLED PRODUCT AS WELL AS CONTAMINATED RAIL BALLAST. THIS SAME FIRM LATER DISPOSED OF THE MATERIAL AS NON-HAZARDOUS WASTE.  ALL PROPER NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE BY RSI LEASING.  SINCE THE RELEASE WE HAVE IMPLEMENTED POLICIES THAT REQUIRE ANY RAILCAR LOADING TO BE COMPLETED THROUGH THE OPEN DOME OF THE CAR RATHER THAN THE VALVED STANDPIPE.  THIS PERMITS THE OPERATOR TO MAINTAIN A VISUAL REFERENCE OF THE LIQUID LEVEL IN THE TANKCAR AND PREVENT AN OVERFILL SITUATION.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: At approximately 6 AM, a fork truck operator was unloading a chemical truck containing waste water treatment chemicals. The operator was trying to pick up a tote and inadvertantly had the end of the forks under the sulfuric acid tote which was behind the tote the operator was unloading. When the operator raised the load, the front of the second tote was lifted off the ground. The operator then backed up, causing the 2nd tote to fall from the forks. The force of the fall caused the front of the tote to crack spilling the entire contents of the tote. The spill came out of the back of the taller and into the storm drain at the loading dock. The spill was completely contained In the storm sewer. The spill response team was contacted and the free liquids were vacuumed up. The trailer and the storm sewer drain were then flushed and the wash water vacuumed up.    A letter was sent to the South Carolina DHEC and USEPA that more fully described the incident, which did not result in a “releaas the term is defined by CERCLA due to the fact that the sulfuric acid spilled was completely contained within the storm sewer and came in contact with no environmental medium.    Concrete storm drain valves were installed at the end of all storm drains at the facility. Only a limited number of fork truck operatos are allowed to unload the waste water chemical shipments.

column168: THE PRODUCT WAS SHIPPED AS 50 FORTY LB BAGS ON ONE SHRINK-WRAPPED PALLETS. WHEN THE DOCKWORKER PICKED UP THE PALLET WITH THE FORKLIFT TO UNLOAD IT FROM P &D TRLR NUMBER 563-8036, HE DISCOVERED A SMALL MOUND OF THE PRODUCT ON THE FLOOR UNDER THE PALLET.  THE SKID WAS TENDERED TO CWX ALREADY LEAKING.  IT WAS NOT OBVIOUS AT THE TIME OF PICKUP AND THE DRIVER COULD NOT SEE IT.  AS THE TRLR MOVED AND BOUNCED DOWN THE ROAD, THE PRODUCT SLOWLY LEAKED THROUGH THE STACKED BAGS ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER.  I MOVED THE DOCK CREW AWAY FROM THE SPILL AND CALLED CHEMTREC AT 1945.  TALKED TO SPENCER AND FILED INCIDENT REPORT 07122004097.  HE HAD DAVE DEBROSKY FROM ADM CALL ME.  HE ADVISED ME THAT WE COULD HANDLE AND PROCEED WITH THE CLEAN UP OURSELVES.  THE PRODUCT WAS LIKE A CONCENTRATED SALT.  IT WAS AN ANIMAL FEED ADDITIVE.  AT THAT TIME I CONTACTED CWX SAFETY DEPT AND TALKED TO JEFF TURNER.  HE ADVISED ME TO PROCEED.  WE CLEANED UP THE SMALL SPILL, PLACED THE PRODUCT IN A RECOVERY DRUM.  THEN RESTACKED THE PALLET OF BAGS, DISCOVERING THREE BAGS WITH TEARS IN THEM, PLACING THEM INTO THE RECOVERY DRUM WITH THE LOOSE PRODUCT.  THE NEXT DAY, 07/13/04, I MADE CONTACT WITH THE SHIPPER, EXPLAINING TO THEM WHAT HAD TRANSPIRED.  THEY DID NOT HESITATE TO ACCEPT THE DAMAGED PRODUCT BACK AND DID NOT CONTEST THE FACTS AS I PRESENTED THEM.  I RETURNED THE DAMAGED BAGS TO THE SHIPPER IN THE RECOVERY DRUM THAT DAY.  THE TORN BAGS WERE NOT HERE MORE THEN 10 HRS.  THE REST OF THE SHIPMENT WENT ON THE BOISE 3 BAGS SHORT.

WE ALSO PUT SOME DOWN AROUND THE VALVE WHERE IT WAS LEAKING.  CALLED SHIPPER AND CHEMTREC.  SHIPPER CAME TO TERMINAL AND TRIED TO FIX IT, COULDN'T STOP LEAK AND THEN TOOK THE TOTE BACK HIMSELF.  WE CLEANED THE TRAILER AND DOCK WITH AMPHO-MAG.  THERE WASN'T ENOUGH SPILLAGE TO PUT IN A CONTAINER.  CHEMTREC'S REPORT NUMBER IS 07142004139.

FRT (3 CTNS) TEMPORARILY DOCKED.  BR FORK TRUCK DRIVER BACKED INTO FRT HARD ENOUGH TO OPEN ONE OF THE 4 GALS INSIDE ONE OF THE CTNS.  DOCKMAN ON FLOOR POSITIONED THE CTN IMMEDIATELY TO RESTRAIN THE LEAKING.  HAD RECOVERY PAIL NEARBY.  ALL 4 GALS IN THE CTN PLUS THE ABSORBING MATERIAL USED TO DRY UP THE SMALL AMT LOST ON DOCK FLOOR, PUT INTO RECOVERY PAIL.  CHEMTREC CONTACTED @ 11:50 AM -- TICKET/REPORT# 07232004-071.  ERTS COMPLIED WITH AT 12:40PM-(CAMERON) SHIPPER AUTHORIZED RETURN OF PRODUCT (106-0050973).

column58: Basic Material; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug)
column168: 07/09/04 @ 1:46 PM, OUR DRIVER, RICHARD LONGSTREET, CALLED IN FROM THE TRUCKSTOP OF AMERICA IN COLUMBIA, NJ.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE TRUCK STOP, HE OPENED HIS TRAILER DOORS TO CHECK HIS LOAD.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE TRUCK STOP, HE OPENED HIS TRAILER DOORS TO CHECK HIS LOAD.  UPON INSPECTION, HE HAD NOTICED FLUID ON A DRUM AND THE TRAILER FLOOR.  HE CALLED IN OUR OFFICE TO REPORT AND FOR FURTHER INSTRUCTION.  HE WAS INSTRUCTED TO PUT ON FULL PPE AND CONTAIN THE MATERIAL ON THE TRAILER FLOOR WITH SPEDI DRY AND ABSORBENT BOOMS.  HE WAS THEN INSTRUCTED TO MOVE THE TRAILER TO THE BACK OF THE LOT AND SET UP HIS TRIANGLES.  I CALLED THE TA FUEL DESK TO HAVE THEM PUT UP CONES 25' AHEAD OF THE TRAILER TO SECURE THE AREA FROM ALL SIDES. LISA BRUCE TOOK THE CALL AND REQUESTED THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE NUMBER FROM THE PAPERWORK.  THE GENERATOR EMERGENCY RESPONSE NUMBER WAS NOT LISTED.  HE GAVE ME THE NUMBER FOR THE GENERATOR.  AFTER SEVERAL ATTEMPTS TO REACH COMPLIANCE PERSONNEL, IT WAS DETERMINED BY THE CTDEP AND LISA BRUCE TO SEND A RESPONSE CREW OUT.  HMHTTC ARRIVED AT THE SCENE AT APPROXIMATELY 4:30 PM ON 7/9/04 AND DETERMINED PIN HOLES ON DRUM AND A CRUSHED SEAL CAUSED THE MATERIAL TO LEAK.  DRUM WAS OVERPACKED AND CONTINUED TRANSPORTATION TO DISPOSAL FACILITY.  DRIVER WAS RELEASED AT APPROX 6:00 PM.  LB.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE TRAVELING ON THE BLUEGRASS PARKWAY WEST, AT MILEPOST 44, THE SLAY TRANSPORTATION COMPANY, INC. DRIVER SWERVED TO AVOID SOME DEER AND THE CARGO TANKER OVERTURNED.  APPROXIMATELY TEN GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AS WELL AS FIVE GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL AND TWO QUARTS OF MOTOR OIL.  THE KENTUCKY DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION, KENTUCKY HIGHWAY PATROL, WILLISBURG FIRE DEPARTMENT, STATE FIRE MARSHALL'S OFFICE, KENTUCKY NATURAL RESOURCES AND ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION CABINET AND MR. JAMES CROUCH OF THE WASHINGTON COUNTY LEPC WERE ALL NOTIFIED OF THE RELEASE AND RESPONDED TO ASSESS THE SITUATION.  THE STATE FIRE MARSHALL'S OFFICE AND KENTUCKY NATURAL RESOURCES AND ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION CABINET APPLIED ABSORBENT PADS TO CONTAIN THE FREE PRODUCT.  AMERICAN ENVIRO-SERVICES, INC., OF SHELBYVILLE, KENTUCKY WAS CONTRACTED TO COMPLETE THE CLEANUP.  BAYER CORPORATION, THE SHIPPER, WAS CONTACTED AND RESPONDED WITH A PUMP TO TRANSFER THE PRODUCT INTO A NEW CARGO TANKER.  AMERICAN ENVIRO-SERVICES, INC. APPLIED ADDITIONAL ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO HELP FURTHER CONTAIN AND REMOVE THE FREE PRODUCT FROM THE AFFECTED ROAD SURFACE.  AMERICAN ENVIRO-SERVICES, INC. USED A MINI-EXCAVATOR TO REMOVE ALL THE IMPACTED SOIL FROM THE SITE.  APPROXIMATELY 1.5 YARDS OF IMPACTED SOIL AND IMPACTED ABSORBENT MATERIALS WERE TRANSPORTED TO THE CENTRAL KENTUCKY LANDFILL IN GEORGETOWN, KENTUCKY FOR PROPER DISPOSAL VIA LANDFILL.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.  THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER, ALL STATE AND LOCAL REGULATORY AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED OF THE RELEASE.

column168: WHEN TRAILER DOOR WAS OPENED THERE WAS A VERY STRONG ODOR.  I CALLED AL ROTH (SAFETY SUPERVISOR).  HE ADVISED ME TO CALL THE 1-800 NUMBER FOR THE SHIPPER.  I CALLED THE SHIPPER # AND TALKED WITH ARJUNO BOWER AND GAVE HIM THE INFORMATION.  HE SAID IT WAS OK TO CLEAN UP.  I HAD THE TRAILER PULLED FROM THE DOCK TO ALLOW THE TRAILER TO AIR OUT.  AFTER A COUPLE OF HOURS WE COULD GET INTO THE TRAILER TO FIND THE LEAK.  THE LOADER DID NOT USE PROPER DUNNAGE BETWEEN PALLETS AND A PALLET SKID OVER AND PUNCTURED A 5 GALLON DRUM.

FILE: 3720 D, SHIPPER: MAPLE LEAF FARM ASSOC, AWB#: BTV 2589982043 PVD  ON 07/31/04 AT 0140 AN INSIDE LEAKING LAB PACK WAS REPORTED IN "A" BUILDING (EXPRESS AREA, LATERAL 31) OF OUR MAIN SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177.  PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIAN MICHAEL JOHNSON DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL HE FOUND A PLASTIC LAB PACK WITH NO VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGE.  HE REMOVED THE LAB PACK FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN HIS INVESTIGATION.  UPON INVESTIGATION HE FOUND THIS LAB PACK TO CONTAIN 5 PLASTIC SPECIMEN CUPS IN A PLASTIC BAG THAT CONTAINED AN UNKNOWN LIQUID. THE CLOSURES ON THESE CUPS WERE NOT SECURED BY POSITIVE MEANS.  THE CLOSURE ON ONE CUP CAME LOOSE ALLOWING IT TO LEAK APPROXIMATELY 15 MLS OF IT'S CONTENTS.  THIS LEAK WAS CONTAINED INSIDE OF THE LAB PACK.  THIS PACKAGE ARRIVED IN WILMINGTON ON FLYT# 0153, N906AX.  THIS LAB PACK WAS MARKED "OVERWRAP FOR DIAGNOSTIC SPECIMEN SHIPMENTS".  AS A PRECAUTION, THE AREA INVOLVED WAS THOROUGHLY CLEANED WITH BLEACH BEFORE NORMAL OPERATIONS WERE RESUMED.  THE PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIAN SEALED AND BAGGED THE LAB PACK IN TWO PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED IT INTO A SALVAGE DRUM. THIS SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO ITS DESTINATION.  CLEAR OF SCENE: 0140 THERE ARE PICTURES ON FILE IN THE HAZ MAT OFFICE IN WILMINGTON, OHIO.

CHEMTREC NOTIFIED CSX TRANSPORTATION'S POLICE COMMUNICATION CENTER THAT THE NORFOLK SOUTHERN (NS) RAILROAD HAD REPORTED A LEAKING TANK CAR IN A CSXT TRAIN IN THE NS RAIL YARD IN CHARLESTON, SC.  GATX28757, LOAD WASTE FLAMMABLE LIQUID N.O.S., WAS REPORTED TO BE LEAKING FROM THE TOP WHEN IT WAS MOVED.  CHEMTREC NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER, SOUTHEASTERN CHEMICALS. INFORMATION PROVED BY NS OFFICIALS AND SOUTHEASTERN CHEMICALS REVEALED THAT FRA INSPECTOR, DAVE SNYDER, WAS CONDUCTING A ROUTINE INSPECTION AT THE NS YARD.  AS CSXT'S TRAIN F75922 WAS PASSING THROUGH THE YARD, MR. SNYDER OBSERVED GATX28757 TO BE WET AROUND THE MANWAY.  HE DIRECTED THE CSXT TRAIN CREW TO SET THE CAR OUT IN THE NS YARD.  NS OFFICIALS CONTACTED CSXT TO OBTAIN SHIPPING PAPERS FOR THE CAR AND THEY NOTIFIED CHEMTREC TO MAKE CONTACT WITH SOUTHEASTERN CHEMICAL.  SOUTHEASTERN CHEMICALS SENT RESCAR, A RAILCAR COMPANY, TO REPAIR THE TANK CAR.  SOUTHEASTERN CHEMICAL ADVISED THAT RESCAR FOUND THAT PRODUCT HAD SLOSHED OUT OF THE MANWAY BECAUSE THE MANWAY COVER GASKET WAS MISSING.  A NEW MANWAY COVER GASKET WAS INSTALLED, THE MANWAY COVER SECURED, AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

column168: JIM SWEENEY, HEAD CLERK, REPORTED A LEAKING CONTAINER CSXU 983995, AT THE CITY OF INDUSTRY INTERMODAL RAMP LOCATED AT 17225 E ARENTH STREET, CITY OF INDUSTRY, CA.  MR. SWEENEY STATED THE CONTAINER BILLING SHOWED THE CONTENTS TO BE A MIXED HAZARDOUS FREIGHT.  A TWO FOOT WIDE PUDDLE, APPROXIMATELY 2 GALLONS, HAD ACCUMULATED UNDER THE CONTAINER WHILE PARKED IN STALL BLUE 720.  DEAN COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  MANAGER COOPER INSPECTED THE CONTAINER AND FOUND APPROXIMATELY SEVENTY FIVE GALLONS OF A PRODUCT IDENTIFIED AS CHLOR FOAM, A SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTION USED AS A LIQUID DETERGENT, HAD LEAKED FROM A 275 GALLON IBC POLY TOTE, DUE TO A DEFECTIVE VALVE CLOSURE AND SECUREMENT CAP.  THE TOTE WAS CONTINUING TO LEAK SEVERAL DROPS PER MINUTE. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO TRANSFER THE REMAINING PRODUCT INTO 55 GALLON POLY DRUMS.  THE TOTE WAS INSPECTED AFTER BEING EMPTIED, AND NO VISIBLE DEFECTS WERE NOTED TO THE VALVE CLOSURE, BUT SUSPECT THE CLOSURE WAS DEFECTIVE AS IT ALLOWED PRODUCT TO BY PASS IN THE CLOSED POSITION.  THE SECUREMENT CAP ALSO FAILED DUE TO STRIPPED PLASTIC THREADS ALLOWING PRODUCT TO BY PASS.  THE DAMAGED TOTE WAS PLACED ON TOP OF AN ADJACENT TOTE TO PROVIDE FLOOR SPACE FOR THE 4 POLY DRUMS OF PRODUCT.  THE FLOORING WAS CLEANED OF THE RESIDUE, AND THE LOADING BLOCKED AND BRACED FOR MOVEMENT OVER THE ROAD TO THE FLOOR.  THIS IS NOT AN ACCEPTABLE METHOD, NOR IS IT AN APPROVED METHOD BY THE AAR BOE PHAMPLET 6C FOR THE SECUREMENT OF HAZARDOUS COMMODITIES IN RAIL TRANSPORTATION.  IT WAS NOTED THE LEAKING TOTE CONTAINED A CORROSIVE LABEL, WHERE AS THE ACCOMPANYING PACKING SLIP LISTED THIS COMMODITY AS AN ORM-D.  ADDITIONALLY, THIS PARTICULAR TOTE CONTAINING THE CHLOR FOAM WAS NOT LISTED ON THE RAIL BILLING ALONG WITH THE OTHER HAZARDOUS COMMODITIES.

RMCC CONTACTED CTS MGR. M. KELLY AND ADVISED THAT THE ABOVE CAR HAD BEEN OBSERVED VENTING VAPORS IN THE FT. WORTH, CENTENNIAL YARD.  KELLY INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THAT IT HAD 70PSI ON THE GAUGE AND THAT IT HAD RELEASED THROUGH THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE.  KELLY CONTACTED THE SHIPPER BAKER PETROLITE AND IT WAS DECIDED THAT THE PRESSURE IN THE CAR SHOULD BE REDUCED TO PREVENT ANOTHER RELEASE.  KELLY SET UP A FLARE AND REDUCED THE PRESSURE IN THE CAR TO 2PSI.  KELLY INSPECTED SEVERAL OTHER ETHYLENE CARS IN THE YARD AND FOUND PTRX 7017 TO HAVE 64 PSI KELLY ALSO FLARED THIS CAR TO 2PSI. BOTH CARS WERE RELEASED TO CONTINUE ONTO THEIR DESTINATION.
