column168: AT 1733HRS ON 7-15-04, CTS MGR. LERCH WAS CONTACTED BY THE RMCC AND ADVISED THAT THE LAKE CHARLES YARDMASTER HAD REPORTED A SWITCHMAN WORKING LOCAL JOB YAK52-15 HAD REPORTED A STRONG AMMONIA ODOR COMING FROM TANK CAR GATX 51998.  THE TANK CAR WAS LOCATED IN TRACK 5.  NOTIFICATIONS HAD ALSO BEEN MADE TO SPECIAL AGENT JIM HERRING, WHO UPON CLOSER INSPECTION OF THE CAR, CONFIRMED AN ODOR OF AMMONIA AROUND THE CAR.  UPON BEING ADVISED OF THE RELEASE, MGR. LERCH REQUESTED NOTIFICATIONS TO BE MADE TO LOUISIANA STATE POLICE., AND THE SHIPPER: TRIAD NITROGEN: VIA CHEM-TREC.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1800HRS MGR. LERCH SPOKE TO DAVID OUBRE, MANAGER OF SAFETY & ENVIRONMENT OF TRAID NITROGEN.  UPON ADVISING MR OUBRE OF THE RELEASE, HE INDICATED THAT HE WOULD BE RESPONDING WITH PLANT PERSONNEL TO INSPECT, TAKE CORRECTIVE ACTION AND TO MAKE NECESSARY REPAIRS TO THE LEAKING CAR.  WHILE ENROUTE MGR. LERCH SPOKE TO LOCAL STATE POLICE WHO ADVISED THAT WERE ON SITE WITH LOUISIANA DEPT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY, MONITORING THE CAR.  STATE POLICE ADVISED THAT AFTER FURTHER INSPECTION OF ADDITIONAL CARS ON THE SAME TRACK, A SECOND CAR, GATX51978, LOADED WITH ANHYDROUS AMMONIA FROM THE SAME SHIPPER WAS NOTED TO BE LEAKING VAPOR.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SCENE, AND IN COMPANY WITH SHIPPER PERSONNEL.  CARS GATX 51998 & GATX 51978 WERE INSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE LEAKING VAPOR FROM THE PRESSURE PLATES OF BOTH CARS.  WITH USE OF APPROPRIATE TOOLS, PRESSURE PLATE BOLTS TO BOTH CARS WERE TIGHTENED APPROXIMATELY 1/8 TO 1/2 TURN WHICH SECURED THE CARS FROM FURTHER RELEASE.  UPON TIGHTENING OF THE BOLTS AND STOPPING RELEASE OF PRODUCT, CAR WERE RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.  AFTER SECURING THE CARS, IT WAS LEARNED THAT THE EMPLOYEE WHO HAD ORIGINALLY REPORTED THE INCIDENT, HAD LATER COMPLAINED OF HEADACHE AND DIZZINESS.  HE WAS TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL FOR A CHECK UP AND WAS RELEASED. HE RETURNED TO WORK THE FOLLOWING DAY.  THERE WERE NO DRAINS OR WATERWAYS IMPACTED FROM THIS RELEASE.

UPON TIGHTENING OF THE BOLTS AND STOPPING RELEASE OF PRODUCT, CAR WERE RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.  AFTER SECURING THE CARS, IT WAS LEARNED THAT THE EMPLOYEE WHO HAD ORIGINALLY REPORTED THE INCIDENT, HAD LATER COMPLAINED OF HEADACHE AND DIZZINESS.  HE WAS TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL FOR A CHECK UP AND WAS RELEASED. HE RETURNED TO WORK THE FOLLOWING DAY.  THERE WERE NO DRAINS OR WATERWAYS IMPACTED FROM THIS RELEASE.

AT 8:55 AM ON FRIDAY, JULY 30, 2004.  I RECEIVED A CALL FROM HOUSTON SHUTTLE DRIVER JIM BOYLE.  HE WAS ON HIS RETURN TRIP FROM THE SAN ANTONIO BRANCH TO THE HOUSTON BRANCH.  JIM INFORMED ME HE HAD A SERIOUS HYDROCHLORIC ACID LEAK ON HWY 59 NEAR SUGARLAND, TX.  HE HAD NOTICED WHAT APPEARED TO BE SMOKE COMING FROM THE BACK OF THE TRAILER AS HE WAS TRAVELING NORTHBOUND ON HWY 59.  AT FIRST HE THOUGHT IT WAS HIS BRAKES OVERHEATING.  BUT WHEN HE STOPPED HE QUICKLY REALIZED IT WAS HCL LEAKING FROM THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  A FT. BEND COUNTY SHERIFF HAPPENED BY AS JIM HAD PULLED OVER AN ABANDONED STATE TRUCK WEIGH SCALE.  JIM AND THE SHERIFF WERE CAREFUL TO KEEP AWAY FROM THE VAPOR CLOUD.  THE SHERIFF CONTACTED THE EMERGENCY AUTHORITIES.  I SPOKE WITH THE SHERIFF AT 9:05 AM TO GET DIRECTIONS TO THE SCENE OF THE INCIDENT. ALAN MORGAN AND I LEFT THE BRANCH AT 9:15 AM. AT APPROXIMATELY 9:30 AM US HWY 59 WAS CLOSED DOWN IN BOTH DIRECTIONS BETWEEN WILLIAMS WAY AND CRAB RIVER RD.  BOTH OUR DRIVER, JIM AND THE FT. BEND COUNTY SHERIFF WERE DECONTAMINATED AT THE SCENE, EVEN THOUGH NEITHER JIM NOR THE SHERIFF FELT IT WAS NECESSARY.  JIM REFUSED BEING TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL AS HE INSISTED HE DID NOT COME INTO CONTACT WITH VAPORS OR LIQUID.  THE SHERIFF WAS TAKEN TO THE ER AS A PRECAUTION, WHICH IS DEPARTMENT PROTOCOL.  AT 9:43 AM I CONTACTED MIKE HARRINGTON IN DALLAS, AS THE PORTABLE TANK THAT FAILED BELONGED TO SAN ANTONIO CUSTOMER HAYES ENERGY.  AT 9:55 I SPOKE WITH MR. DANNY JAN, THE FORT BEND COUNTY EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT ASSISTANT COORDINATOR.  MR. JAN ADVISED WE WOULD NEED TO CALL IN SOMEONE FOR CLEAN-UP AND DECONTAMINATION.  AT 10:05 AM I CONTACTED CORY ANDERSON WITH HULCHER SERVICES INC AND ADVISED THEM OF THE ASSISTANCE NEEDED RELATING TO THIS INCIDENT.  I LEFT MR. JAN'S CELL PHONE NUMBER WITH CORY AND ASKED CORY TO CONTACT MR. JAN DIRECTLY TO KEEP HIM APPRISED OF THEIR ETA.  I ALSO CONTACTED MR. JAN AND LEFT A MESSAGE ON HIS VOICEMAIL WITH CORY'S NAME AND CELL PHONE NUMBER SO HE COULD CONTACT CORY IF NECESSARY, AND TO INFORM HIM THAT HULCHER WAS ENROUTE.  AT APPROXIMATELY 10:45 AM ALAN AND I ARRIVED AT THE COMMAND CENTER.  WE WERE INTRODUCED TO MR. JAN AND JAVIER CRESPO WHO WAS THE INCIDENT COMMANDER.  WE WERE ADVISED A "REVERSE 911" WAS ISSUED FOR A NEIGHBORHOOD ON THE EAST SIDE OF HWY 59. THIS INCLUDED INFORMING RESIDENTS OF A "SHELTER IN PLACE" ORDER THAT WAS ISSUED.  THE CLOSEST HOSES TO THE SCENE WERE APPROXIMATELY 500 YARDS. THERE WERE NO NEARBY BUSINESSES AND NO INJURIES WERE REPORTED AT THIS TIME. THE "SHELTER IN PLACE" ORDER WAS LIFTED AROUND 11:00 AM.  THE INCIDENT COMMANDER WAS AT THIS TIME WAITING ON THE CLEAN-UP TEAM (HULCHER) TO ARRIVE.  HULCHER ARRIVED AT THE SCENE AT APPROXIMATELY 11:10 AM.  AT 11:20 AM REPRESENTATIVES FROM UNIVAR (ALAN AND I), CORY ANDERSON AND ERIC VERING WITH HULCHER, DANNY JAN AND JAVIER CRESPO MET AT THE COMMAND CENTER TO DEVELOP A PLAN OF ACTION FOR CLEAN-UP AND DECONTAMINATION OF THE HIGHWAY AND EQUIPMENT.  AT 11:45

column168: ON THE MORNING OF 7.28.04 AIRCRAFT #856AA, FLT.# 735 WAS ENROUTE TO PH TO RECOVER FREIGHT AND THEN PROCEED TO FWA INDIANA.  WHILE IN FLIGHT CREWMEMBERS NOTICED A NOXIOUS ODOR COMING FROM THE CARGO AREA AND STARTED EXPERIENCING IRRITATION OF THE EYES AND HAVING BREATHING CONCERNS.  TWO OF THE THREE MEMBERS HAD TO USE THE AID OF OXYGEN ON THE LAST STAGE OF THE FLIGHT.  UPON ARRIVAL (0120 HRS.) JOE CIOCCO (PM SUPV.) NOTICED A NOXIOUS ODOR AS HE OPENED AIRCRAFT DOOR; AND OBSERVED THE CREW IN SOME DISCOMFORT AS THEY EXITED AIRCRAFT.  AFTER AIRCRAFT WAS OPENED UP, THE CREW WITH MAINTENANCE AND JOE CIOCCO INSPECTED AIRCRAFT AND DETERMINED WHERE SOURCE OF ODOR WAS.  IT WAS A BLACK CRATE (1) THAT WAS PART OF A LARGER SHIPMENT INCLUDING (5) OTHER PIECES SPREAD OUT ON (3) ULD'S TOTAL.  DAVE LASASSO (MX) STATED HE SAW "FUEL DRIPPING FROM THE CASE" AND JOE CIOCCO NOTICED "NOXIOUS ODOR AND VISUAL LEAKAGE".  (0130 HRS) KITTYHAWK'S OPERATION DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED AND (MATT HOWARD) INSTRUCTED JOE CIOCCO TO DOWNLOAD AIRCRAFT AND TO REMOVE ALL (6) PIECES FROM THE (3) ULD'S.  AT (0145 HRS.) THE DOWNLOAD WAS COMPLETED AND IT WAS NOTED THAT (3) CRATES WERE LOADED ON END, BUT NEITHER ONE HAD ANY DIRECTIONAL LABELS ON ANY SIDE OR WARNING LABELS OF THE CONTENTS THEREIN.  AIRCRAFT WAS RELOADED, LESS THE (6) PIECES AND FLEW TO FWA.  IT WAS DECIDED AT KHA OPS. TO GET EVERYBODY INVOLVED IN THE AM.  (0630 HRS.) I, DAN DALY (STATION MGR.) RECEIVED A CALL FROM KHA OPS. (TONY MILLER) ALERTING ME THAT THE AIRPORT FIRE DEPT. WAS ON THEIR WAY TO INSPECT THE CRATE THAT WAS LEAKING AND EMITTING ODOR.  (0700 HRS.) THE FIRE DEPT. ARRIVED AND INSPECTED THE OUTSIDE OF THE CRATE.  I POINTED OUT WHAT APPEARED TO BE A STAIN ON TOP OF CRATE, BUT COULD NOT SMELL AN ODOR AT THE TIME.  SINCE IT WAS NOT LEAKING THE FIRE DEPT COULD NOT GO ANY FURTHER AND LEFT AFTER EXPLAINING THAT THEY CANNOT OPEN CONTAINERS IF THEY ARE UNDECLARED SHIPMENTS.  (1030 HRS.) AFTER A FEW HOURS IT WAS DECIDED BY DEWEY BETHEL (HAZ-MAT SPECIALIST KHA) AND MYSELF THAT I WOULD INSPECT THE CONTENTS TO GIVE A PRELIMINARY REPORT TO KHA OPS.  UPON OPENING CRATE AN OVERWHELMING ODOR CAME OUT AND WE HAD TO STEP AWAY UNTIL IT DISSIPATED. WE, BEING DAN ORT (GSE MX) AND MYSELF.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE CONTENTS WERE MINIATURE AIRCRAFT (RADIO CONTROLLED) THAT HAD FUEL TANKS.  INSIDE THE CRATE THAT LEAKED WAS AN AIRCRAFT THAT HAD FUEL IN THE FUEL LINES, BUT WE COULD NOT DETERMINE IF THE TANK HAD BEEN FULL OR NOT.  FROM INFORMATION GATHERED, IT SEEMED TO BE FULL OR PARTIALLY FULL, AND AFTER THE LEAKAGE THE FUEL VAPORIZED, ONLY LEAVING A STAIN AND ODOR.  PICTURES WERE TAKEN AND SENT TO KHA.  THE D.O.T. FORM F 5000.01 WAS FILLED OUT AND IS ON HAND FOR FAA INSPECTION.  THIS INFORMATION WAS GATHERED FROM EMPLOYEES WORKING AT THE PHL STATION ON THE MORNING OF 7/28/04.

column168: DOCK WORKER WAS UNLOADING TRAILER AND ACCIDENTLY HIT THE DRUM WITH FORKLIFT BLADE CAUSING THE DRUM TO BE PUNCTURED AND LOSE ENTIRE CONTENT.  DOCK WORKER PUT AN ABSORBENT ON SPILLED MATERIAL. A HAZMAT CLEANUP CREW WAS CALLED IN TO CLEAN UP THE SPILLED MATERIAL. THE RESIN HAD SPILLED ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR AND HAD LEAKED ONTO THE PAVED PARKING AREA AT THE DOCK. THE HAZMAT CREW APPLIED ADDITIONAL ABSORBENT TO IMPACTED AREAS AND THEN COLLECTED THE MATERIAL IN A DRUM. THE PAVED PARKING AREA WAS SANDED WITH AN INDUSTRIAL CONCRETE SANDER TO REMOVE THE RESIN STAIN

THE DRIVER FOR CTL WAS DELIVERING A LOAD OF STYRENE RESIN TO CORSTONE INC. IN GREENVILLE, AL.  THE DRIVER FOR CTL WAS GIVEN AUTHORIZATION TO BEGIN UNLOADING IN THE PLANTS MAIN STORAGE TANK.  ANNA BOUTWELL REMOVED THE LOCK FROM THE CUSTOMER'S UNLOADING VALVE IN ORDER FOR THE DELIVERY TO TAKE PLACE.  ONCE THE OFF-LOADING PROCESS THE PLANT OPERATOR MADE THE DETERMINATION THAT THE TANK WOULD NOT HOLD THE ENTIRE SHIPMENT OF PRODUCT BEING DELIVERED.  AT THIS PAINT THE UNLOADING PROCESS WAS STOPPED AND PORTABLE TOTES WHERE PUT IN PLACE TO FINISH THE OFF-LOADING PROCESS.  THE BALANCE OF THE PRODUCT WOULD NOW HAVE TO BE DRUMMED OFF USING A DRUMMING NOZZLE.  THE DRIVER UNHOOKED FROM THE MAIN RECEIVING TANK AND ATTACHED A DRUMMING NOZZLE AND PLACED THE DRUMMING NOZZLE INTO THE TOP OF THE TOTE. ANNA BOUTWELL THE PLANT OPERATOR INSTRUCTED THE DRIVER FOR CTL THAT HE WOULD NEED TO OPERATOR THE TRACTOR PUMP AND SHE WOULD OPERATE THE DRUMMING NOZZLE.  THE DRUMMING NOZZLE WAS PLACED IN THE OPEN POSITION AND THE CTL DRIVER THEN ENGAGED THE TRACTOR PUMP AFTER HE WAS GIVEN THE OK BY ANNA BOUTWELL STATING THAT SHE WAS READY TO OFF-LOAD THE BALANCE OF THE PRODUCT REMAINING IN THE CARGO TANK INTO THE PORTABLE TOTE.  ONCE THE PRODUCT STARTED TO FLOW THROUGH THE PUMP INTO THE OFF LOADING LINE IT BECAME VERY DIFFICULT FOR ANNA BOUTWELL TO HOLD ONTO THE END OF THE DRUMMING NOZZLE. THE DRIVER FOR CTL IMMEDIATELY SHUT THE TRACTOR PUMP OFF.  ANNA BOUTWELL COULD NOT CONTROL THE END OF THE OFF-LOADING LINE AND THE OFF-LOADING LINE GOT AWAY FROM HER AND SHE WAS EXPOSED TO THE PRODUCT.  ANNA BOUTWELL FELT A MILD BURNING SENSATION FROM THE PRODUCT AND IMMEDIATELY WAS PLACE UNDER THE SAFETY SHOWER.  ANNA BOUTWELL WAS TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL AS PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE AND WAS SEEN BY THE EMERGENCY ROOM DOCTOR AT STABLER HOSPITAL. ACCORDING TO THE EMERGENCY ROOM DOCTOR ANNA BOUTWELL HAD A MILD IRRITATION AND WAS NOT INJURED IN ANY WAY.  SHE WAS DISCHARGED FROM THE HOSPITAL AND RETURNED IMMEDIATELY BACK TO HER JOB THE SAME DAY.  ANNA BOUTWELL STATED THAT SHE DID NOT ANTICIPATE THAT THERE WOULD BE A NEED FOR HER TO SEE A DOCTOR AGAIN WITH REGARD TO THIS INCIDENT.

AARON WAS ISSUED AN LOI FOR THE INCIDENT.

AT 1105HR ON 7-16-04, CTS MGR LERCH WAS CONTACTED BY THE RMCC AND ADVISED THAT GEORGE DAVIS, SENIOR MANAGER INTERMODAL OPERATIONS HAD REPORTED LOADED INTERMODAL CONTAINER UTCU 462696 TO BE LEAKING.  UPON ARRIVAL AND INSPECTION OF CONTAINER, MGR LERCH NOTED CONTAINER TO BE LEAKING FROM A CRACK IN THE SHELL NEAR THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  PRODUCT WAS LEAKING AT A RATE OF APPROXIMATELY ONE QUART AN HOUR WITH LESS THAN ONE GALLON RELEASED. ABSORBENT MATERIAL HAD BEEN APPLIED BY INTERMODAL PERSONNEL TO CONTAIN THE RELEASE.  MGR LERCH REQUESTED RMCC TO MAKE SHIPPER NOTIFICATION VIA CHEM-TREC.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1145HRS MGR LERCH SPOKE TO JOHN CARIO, MGR HEALTH & SAFETY OF STOLTZ TRUCKING ADVISING HIM THE NATURE OF THE RELEASE. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO HAVE STOLTZ PERSONNEL RESPOND AND TRANSFER PRODUCT FROM THE LEAKING CONTAINER INTO CONTAINER RMCU 114085.  UPON COMPLETION OF THE TRANSFER, A TEMPORARY PATCH WAS SECURED TO THE LEAKING CONTAINER AND BOTH CONTAINERS WERE THEN TRANSPORTED.  STOLTZ TRUCKING TERMINAL LOCATED IN CHANNELVIEW, TX.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WHICH WAS CONTAINED WITHIN THE ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS RECOVERED AND DISPOSED OF BY STOLTZ PERSONNEL.  THERE WERE NO DRAINS, WATERWAYS, OR REPORTED INJURIES RESULTING FROM THIS RELEASE.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 0140 HRS ON 7-21-04, CTS MGR LERCH WAS CONTACTED BY THE RMCC AND ADVISED THAT TRAIN CREW ON TRAIN MB-THO-19 HAD REPORTED A UNINDENTIFIABLE ODOR COMING FROM A PARKED TRAIN MNOEW-18 LOCATED IN THE SIDING TRACK AT AMES, TX; MILEPOST 317.54 CONSIST SHOWED NUMEROUS CARS OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS ON TRAIN MNOEW-18.  MGR LERCH TOGETHER WITH MGR YARD OPERATIONS RAY HARE, NOTED THE 36TH CAR FROM THE HEAD END TO BE VENTING VAPOR.  AFTER IDENTIFYING THE VENTING CAR, MGT LERCH INSTRUCTED RMCC TO MAKE SHIPPER AND APPROPRIATE AGENCY NOTIFICATIONS.  ADDITIONAL NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO LOCAL EMERGENCY SERVICES TO SHUT DOWN ACCESS TO BUSINESSES AND HIGHWAYS IN THE IMMEDIATE AREA., CENTER FOR TOXICOLOGY AND ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH, THE CONSIGNEE OXY VINYL OF LA PORTE, TX, AND MGR SITE REMEDIATION, GEOFF REEDER.  AFTER MAKING NOTIFICATIONS, MGR LERCH TOOK AN AIR SAMPLE WITH GAS-TEC CHLORINE DETECTION TUBE, APPROXIMATELY 100 YARDS SOUTH OF THE CAR.  READING FROM THE TUBE WAS UNDETECTABLE.  ON ARRIVAL OF OXY VINYL CHLOR-REP RESPONSE PERSONNEL, AN INSPECTION OF THE CAR WAS CONDUCTED NOTING PRODUCT VENTING FROM THE PRESSURE PLATE.  AFTER DETERMINING SOURCE OF RELEASE, SEVERAL ATTEMPTS WERE MADE TO STOP THE RELEASE BY TIGHTENING OF THE PRESSURE PLATE BOLTS.  WITH EACH ATTEMPT MADE, THE RELEASE WAS SLOWED.  AFTER MINIMIZING THE RELEASE, A FINAL ATTEMPT WAS CONDUCTED AND COMPLETED WITH THE SECURING THE CAR FROM FURTHER RELEASE. ALL BOLTS ON THE PRESSURE PLATE TIGHTENED APPROXIMATELY 1/8 TO 1/2 TURN EACH.  DURING THE COURSE OF EVENTS TAKING PLACE, AIR MONITORING WAS CONDUCTED BY CTEH.  OXY VINYL AND FIRE PERSONNEL.  AFTER SECURING THE CAR FROM FURTHER RELEASE, AN FRA MOVEMENT APPROVAL WAS ISSUED, #04070199.  CAR WAS TO MOVE UNDER THE PROVISIONS PRESCRIBED IN THE PERMIT FROM AMES, TX TO OXY VINYL, LA PORTE, TX,; TO BE IMMEDIATELY OFF LOADED.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1135 HRS THE AREA WAS CLEARED AND ACCESS TO HIGHWAYS AND BUSINESSES WERE OPENED.  CAR DEPARTED FROM AMES, TX; AND ARRIVED AT OXY VINYL, LA PORTE, TX; AT APPROXIMATELY 1735HRS.  CAR SBLX 14150 WAS BROUGHT INTO THE OXY VINYL FACILITY FOR OFF LOADING AND HANDLING BY THE SHIPPER AND OXY VINYL.

column42: ACETIC ACID, GLACIAL OR ACETIC ACID SOLUTION, WITH MORE THAN 80 PERCENT ACID, BY MASS
column168: AT 2315 ON 7-27-04, CTS MGR LERCH WAS CONTACTED BY THE RMCC AND ADVISED THAT THREE TRAINMEN WERE INJURED WHILE SWITCHING LOADED TANK CELX 6212 IN THE FREEPORT TEXAS YARD.  INJURIES RESULTED FROM PRODUCT SPLASHING OUT FROM THE MAN WAY OPENING, CAUSING SLIGHT BURNS.  LOCAL EMERGENCY MEDICAL SERVICES RESPONDED TO SCENE, AND THE TRAINMEN WERE TAKEN TO A LOCAL HOSPITAL, TREATED AND RELEASED.  MGR LERCH RESPONDED, AND REQUESTED RMCC MAKE SHIPPER NOTIFICATION VIA CHEM-TREC.  AT APPROXIMATELY 0030HRS ON 7-22-04, CTS MGR LERCH WAS CONTACTED BY MR. GREG ALLEN, LOGISTICS MANAGER FOR EASTMAN CHEMICAL.  MGR LERCH ADVISED MR. ALLEN OF THE OCCURRENCE, AND INFORMED HIM THAT HE WAS EN ROUTE TO FURTHER INVESTIGATE.  ON ARRIVAL, MGR LERCH INSPECTED CAR CELX 6212, NOTING ONE MAN WAY SWINGBOLT TO BE STRIPPED AND THE MANWAY GASKET TO BE IN POOR UNSERVICEABLE CONDITION.  MR. ALLEN WAS ADVISED OF THE EXCEPTIONS.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE BY MR ALLEN TO HAVE HULCHER SERVICES CLEAN & DECON THE TANK CAR AND RESCAR MOBIL RAIL REPAIR TO REPLACED THE MANWAY SWINGBOLT.  ONCE ABOVE CORRECTIONS WERE MADE, LERCH THEN REPLACED THE FAILED MANWAY GASKET WITH A GORTEX GASKET, AND HAD ALL MANWAY SWINGBOLTS PROPERLY SECURED BY RESCAR PERSONNEL.  TANK CAR CELX 6212 WAS THEN RELEASED TO CONTINUE ONTO DESTINATION WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT. THERE WERE NO DRAINS, WATERWAYS IMPACTED RESULTING FROM THIS RELEASE.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: AT 0652HRS ON 7-26-04, CTS MGR LERCH WAS CONTACTED BY THE RMCC AND ADVISED THAT BRIAN RICHARD, DIRECTOR OF TERMINAL OPERATIONS, REPORTED TANK CAR TGAX 131335 TO BE LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR.  CAR WAS LOCATED IN BOWL TRACK 14, SETTEGAST YARD; HOUSTON, TX.  UPON RECEIVING INFORMATION MGR LERCH INSTRUCTED RMCC TO MAKE SHIPPER NOTIFICATION VIA CHEM-TREC.  UPON ARRIVAL AND INSPECTION OF THE CAR, MGR LERCH NOTED A SLIGHT AMOUNT OF PRODUCT ON THE TOP AND SIDES OF CAR WHICH HAD DRIED.  THE MANWAY GASKET WAS FOUND TO BE CUT, WORN, AND IN POOR CONDITION.  MGR LERCH REPLACED THE WORN GASKET WITH A NEW NOZZLE GASKET, PROPERLY SECURED THE CAR, AND RELEASED IT FOR TRANSPORTATION.  AT APPROXIMATELY 0730HRS MGR LERCH SPOKE TO LARRY HOPPER, FLEET MAINTENANCE MGR FOR POTASH, ADVISING HIM OF THE NATURE OF THE RELEASE, AND CORRECTIVE ACTION TAKEN.  MR. HOPPER ADVISED THAT HE WOULD FURTHER INVESTIGATE THIS INCIDENT TO PREVENT THIS RECURRENCE.  THERE WERE NO DRAINS, WATERWAYS, OR REPORTED INJURIES RESULTING FROM THIS RELEASE.

column168: AT 1925HRS CTS MGR LERCH WAS CONTACTED BY THE RMCC AND ADVISED THAT RAY HARE, MANAGER OF YARD OPERATIONS HAD REPORTED TANK CAR DOWX 79695 TO BE LEAKING.  AFTER NOTIFICATION, MGR LERCH INSTRUCTED RMCC TO MAKE SHIPPER NOTIFICATION VIA CHEM-TREC.  AFTER ARRIVAL AND INSPECTION OF CAR, MGR LERCH NOTED THE MANWAY GASKET TO BE WORN, BROKEN, AND UNSERVICEABLE.  MGR REPLACED FAULTY GASKET WITH A NEW NOZZLE GASKET, SECURED AND RELEASED THE CAR FOR TRANSPORTATION.  AT APPROXIMATELY 2045HRS MGR LERCH SPOKE TO JERRY DIESE, LOGISTIC MANAGER FOR KMCO, AND ADVISED HIM THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE, AND CORRECTIVE ACTION.  MR. DEISE INDICATED THAT HE WOULD FURTHER INVESTIGATE AND TAKE CORRECTIVE ACTION TO PREVENT THIS RECURRENCE.  THERE WERE NO DRAINS, WATERWAYS, OR REPORTED INJURIES RESULTING FROM THIS RELEASE.  ADDITIONALLY, THERE WAS NO CLEAN-UP REQUIRED, AS RELEASE WAS MINIMAL, AND PRODUCT EVAPORATED UPON CONTACT WITH THE ATMOSPHERE.

DRIVER REPORTS THAT DURING UNLOADING AT RINCHEM, HE AND THE UNLOADER OBSERVED LIQUID ESCAPING THROUGH VENTS IN THE TOPS OF FOUR MINI PORTAFEEDS. HAZMAT REPORTED THE OCCURRENCE TO THE SHIPPER VIA CHEMTREC.  LESLIE OSBORN AT NALCO RETURNED THE CALL AND STATED THAT CLEAN UP CONTRACTOR HULCHER SERVICES IS AT RINCHEM AT THIS TIME, WORKING ON A SEPARATE NALCO INCIDENT. STEVE SCHIESL AT NALCO CALLED AND SAID THAT RINCHEM HAD CALLED THIS INCIDENT INTO HIM VIA CHEMTREC A SHORT TIME EARLIER.  MR. SCHIESL ADVISED HAZMAT THAT HE WILL INSTRUCT HULCHER TO HANDLE THIS ONE AS WELL.  DRIVER CALLED BACK AT 1430 TO REPORT THAT HULCHER HAS COMPLETED WORK AND HE HIS DEPARTING.  THE CONSIGNEE HAS ACCEPTED THE SHIPMENT WITH A NOTATION OF ITS CONDITION.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE TRAVELING ON THE BLUEGRASS PARKWAY WEST, AT MILEPOST 44, THE SLAY TRANSPORTATION COMPANY, INC. DRIVER SWERVED TO AVOID SOME DEER AND THE CARGO TANKER OVERTURNED.  APPROXIMATELY TEN GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AS WELL AS FIVE GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL AND TWO QUARTS OF MOTOR OIL.  THE KENTUCKY DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION, KENTUCKY HIGHWAY PATROL, WILLISBURG FIRE DEPARTMENT, STATE FIRE MARSHALL'S OFFICE, KENTUCKY NATURAL RESOURCES AND ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTIONS CABINET AND MR. JAMES CROUCH OF THE WASHINGTON COUNTY LEPC WERE ALL NOTIFIED OF THE RELEASE AND RESPONDED TO ASSESS THE SITUATION.  THE STATE FIRE MARSHALL'S OFFICE AND KENTUCKY NATURAL RESOURCES AND ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION CABINET APPLIED ABSORBENT PADS TO CONTAIN THE FREE PRODUCT.  AMERICAN ENVIRO-SERVICES, INC OF SHELBYVILLE, KENTUCKY WAS CONTRACTED TO COMPLETE THE CLEANUP.  BAYER CORPORATION, THE SHIPPER, WAS CONTACTED AND RESPONDED WITH A PUMP TO TRANSFER THE PRODUCT INTO A NEW CARGO TANKER.  AMERICAN ENVIRO-SERVICES, INC. APPLIED ADDITIONAL ABSORBENT MATERIALS TO HELP FURTHER CONTAIN AND REMOVE THE FREE PRODUCT FROM THE AFFECTED ROAD SURFACE.  AMERICAN ENVIRO-SERVICES, INC. USED A MINI-EXCAVATOR TO REMOVE ALL THE IMPACTED SOIL FROM THE SITE.  APPROXIMATELY 1.5 YARDS OF IMPACTED SOIL AND IMPACTED ABSORBENT MATERIALS WERE TRANSPORTED TO THE CENTRAL KENTUCKY LANDFILL IN GEORGETOWN, KENTUCKY FOR PROPER DISPOSAL VIA LANDFILL.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.  THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER, ALL STATE AND LOCAL REGULATORY AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED OF THE RELEASE.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: CHRIS, YARD MASTER, REPORTED KEVIN MENARD, CAR FOREMAN, DETECTED AN AMMONIA SMELL FROM TANKCAR GATX 51955 IN THE LAKE CHARLES RAILYARD.  HE WAS OVERCOME BY THE VAPORS AND WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE HOSPITAL.  THOMAS ROBINSON, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  AMANDA, LOUISIANA DEPARTMENT OF PUBLIC SAFETY AND DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY AND RON, CHEMTREC REPRESENTATIVE WERE NOTIFIED.  MR. ROBINSON ADVISED THAT MR JOHN PORTER, STATE POLICE EMERGENCY RESPONSE, WAS ON SCENE AND THERE WERE NO OFF SITE AREAS AFFECTED BY THE AMMONIA LEAK. MR. FLACK, NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER, WAS NOTIFIED.  ON 07/07/2004 AT 1:47 AM, ROBINSON ADVISED HE WAS ON SCENE, AS WERE TRIAD NITROGEN PERSONNEL. BOTH ROBINSON AND TRAID PERSONNEL, WEARING APPROPRIATE PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT, INSPECTED THE TANKCAR.  THEY DETERMINED THAT THERE WAS A SLIGHT VAPOR ESCAPING FROM THE PRESSURE PLATE ON THE TANKCAR AND THEY WERE AWAITING ARRIVAL OF HULCHER SERVICES TO AFFECT REPAIR.  AT 04:00 AM, ROBINSON REPORTED THAT THEY HAD TIGHTENED ALL OF THE NUTS ON THE STUDS OF THE PRESSURE PLATE WHICH SECURED THE CAR FROM LEAKING.  THEY CHECKED SIMILAR TANKCARS TO MAKE SURE THE NUTS WERE TIGHT AS WELL.

CRAWFORD, RAMP FOREMAN, REPORTED A RELEASE FROM CONTAINER OOLU 343778, ON RAILCAR CRLE 04032, AT THE RAMP IN SALT LAKE CITY, UT.  ALAN JENSEN, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. LESS THAN FIVE POUNDS OF PRODUCT RELEASED.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES.  PACIFIC WEST, LLC CLEANED UP THE SPILLED PRODUCT AND REPAIRED THE BAGS ON MONDAY MORNING, 07/12/04.  THE CONTAINER WAS RELEASED TO THE SHIPPER.
